00:07:59.825 --> 00:08:00.325
Andrew.

00:08:05.955 --> 00:08:07.580
AUDIENCE: Standard
operating procedure.

00:08:07.580 --> 00:08:09.770
PROFESSOR: Standard
operating procedure.

00:08:09.770 --> 00:08:10.530
I like that.

00:08:10.530 --> 00:08:14.450
Anybody else give me
another word for it, maybe?

00:08:14.450 --> 00:08:17.610
An algorithm.

00:08:17.610 --> 00:08:21.480
So a set of promises
in digital form.

00:08:21.480 --> 00:08:25.970
But it can include math,
basically, if you wish

00:08:25.970 --> 00:08:30.560
or standard operating
procedures-- if-then statements

00:08:30.560 --> 00:08:32.380
and so forth.

00:08:32.380 --> 00:08:36.375
And the parties then perform
against these promises.

00:08:36.375 --> 00:08:37.000
And guess what?

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.640
Nick Szabo wrote that in 1996.

00:08:39.640 --> 00:08:41.770
And I thought it was
still probably the best

00:08:41.770 --> 00:08:44.140
definition of smart contract.

00:08:44.140 --> 00:08:47.440
He coined the
phrase 22 years ago.

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:49.900
He might actually
be Satoshi Nakamoto.

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:52.330
Three of the tables
in here, you all

00:08:52.330 --> 00:08:53.770
voted that it was Nick Szabo.

00:08:56.500 --> 00:08:58.990
So I thought that's kind
of the best definition

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:02.650
