which would mean add $1.

00:13:20.680 --> 00:13:24.580
So Ethereum is account based
and, in fact, doesn't even

00:13:24.580 --> 00:13:26.500
have one programming language.

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:28.840
There's six or seven
programming languages

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:32.970
you can write in, for
those who are so inclined.

00:13:32.970 --> 00:13:38.570
So I'm going to go through
really quickly my analysis,

00:13:38.570 --> 00:13:40.370
and many other
people's, but my sort

00:13:40.370 --> 00:13:43.820
of rendition of the difference
between Ethereum and bitcoin.

00:13:43.820 --> 00:13:45.380
But stop me if
there's a question.

00:13:45.380 --> 00:13:46.750
So the founder.

00:13:46.750 --> 00:13:49.400
There's actually a founder.

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:52.450
The mythology around
Vatalik Buterin

00:13:52.450 --> 00:13:54.870
might not be as great
as Satoshi Nakamoto.

00:13:54.870 --> 00:14:00.500
But a 19-year-old journalist who
was writing about bitcoin for--

00:14:00.500 --> 00:14:04.850
was it Bitcoin Magazine, if I
remember where he was writing--

00:14:04.850 --> 00:14:08.190
said, we can build
something on top

00:14:08.190 --> 00:14:11.630
of it using Nick Szabo's
thoughts about smart contracts,

00:14:11.630 --> 00:14:15.135
about six years after bitcoin.

00:14:18.150 --> 00:14:19.860
He made it Turing complete.

00:14:19.860 --> 00:14:23.670
Does anyone want to remind the
class what Turing complete is?

00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:24.720
Did I see a hand up?

00:14:24.720 --> 00:14:25.890
Yes.

00:14:25.890 --> 00:14:26.455
Bold of you.

00:14:26.455 --> 00:14:27.663
What's your first name again?

00:14:27.663 --> 00:14:28.390
AUDIENCE: Alana.

00:14:28.390 --> 00:14:29.448
PROFESSOR: Alana.

00:14:29.448 --> 00:14:31.490
AUDIENCE: You could write
pretty much any-- well,

00:14:31.490 --> 00:14:33.782
you can write loops, but you
write any kind of program,

00:14:33.782 --> 00:14:35.890
like any form of
logic is expressed.

00:14:35.890 --> 00:14:37.800
PROFESSOR: So Alana
says Turing complete

00:14:37.800 --> 00:14:39.150
means you can write loops.

00:14:39.150 --> 00:14:43.440
But what that really means
for the business crowd is it

00:14:43.440 --> 00:14:46.260
means you can write a program
to do just about anything.

00:14:46.260 --> 00:14:48.180
It's highly flexible.

00:14:48.180 --> 00:14:50.700
I'm sure the technologist in
here will say, well, maybe

00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:52.710
there's something
you can't do with it.

00:14:52.710 --> 00:14:55.170
But the point in
what Vatalik said

00:14:55.170 --> 00:14:58.920
is we shouldn't just limit it
to a scripting language that

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:01.500
was non-Turing
complete that can just

00:15:01.500 --> 00:15:05.310
move a little bit of
peer-to-peer value around,

00:15:05.310 --> 00:15:11.100
that he wanted to do basically
a peer-to-peer virtual computer

00:15:11.100 --> 00:15:14.310
that could move code
and complete code.

00:15:14.310 --> 00:15:16.980
And over the years,
it's being able to be

00:15:16.980 --> 00:15:18.320
written in a bunch of things.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:21.810
But Solidity is the
main program language.

00:15:21.810 --> 00:15:25.170
And thus, it's account based
rather than transaction

00:15:25.170 --> 00:15:27.510
based because of the loops.

00:15:27.510 --> 00:15:31.620
If you could loop and be Turing
complete with transactions,

00:15:31.620 --> 00:15:34.770
there is a vulnerability
in attack factors

00:15:34.770 --> 00:15:38.320
that he made it account based.

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:42.015
The transactions are
stored in Merkle keys.

00:15:42.015 --> 00:15:42.640
But guess what?

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:45.220
If you were really interested
and wanted to learn everything

00:15:45.220 --> 00:15:48.670
about Ethereum, there's at
least four key Merkle trees

00:15:48.670 --> 00:15:52.780
that get summarized up
into the block headers.

00:15:52.780 --> 00:15:55.420
There's the transactions,
which, in essence,

00:15:55.420 --> 00:15:56.500
aren't transactions.

00:15:56.500 --> 00:15:58.780
They call them
state transitions.

00:15:58.780 --> 00:16:01.480
There's the state
itself, something

00:16:01.480 --> 00:16:04.420
called storage, which is
really related to each one

00:16:04.420 --> 00:16:07.390
of the individual Ethereum
accounts, and then,

00:16:07.390 --> 00:16:09.670
believe it or not,
actually, receipts.

00:16:09.670 --> 00:16:12.700
There's written records of
receipts from every state

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:14.530
transition.

00:16:14.530 --> 00:16:19.400
So there's a lot more complexity
inside the Ethereum blockchain.

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:23.510
They run about 14 seconds a
block instead of 10 minutes.

00:16:23.510 --> 00:16:26.600
And that change is a
bunch of the economics.

00:16:26.600 --> 00:16:32.010
Proof of work, for some
reason, which others can study.

00:16:32.010 --> 00:16:35.450
Vatalik decided to use a
different hash function.

00:16:35.450 --> 00:16:37.760
It's still based on
elliptic curves, I think,

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:40.840
but a different hash function.

00:16:40.840 --> 00:16:42.760
What about the economics?

00:16:42.760 --> 00:16:47.680
Well, it's called ETH or E-T-H.
It's programmed in such a way

00:16:47.680 --> 00:16:52.210
that you can't use
ASICs, purposely

00:16:52.210 --> 00:16:55.840
makes it that mining
is more decentralized,

00:16:55.840 --> 00:16:57.580
and you don't have
the big factories.

00:17:00.280 --> 00:17:04.360
The entire hash community,
the entire mining community,

00:17:04.360 --> 00:17:05.770
is much smaller.

00:17:05.770 --> 00:17:06.988
In fact, I think it's about--

00:17:06.988 --> 00:17:07.780
what would that be?

00:17:07.780 --> 00:17:10.270
200,000 times smaller.

00:17:10.270 --> 00:17:15.280
There's 260 terahashes per
second as of yesterday.

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:21.230
And the bitcoin mining
community has 54 exahashes.

00:17:21.230 --> 00:17:23.900
That means lots more computers,
a lot more electricity,

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:28.490
a lot more gnashing of
teeth about resources.

00:17:28.490 --> 00:17:32.060
Bitcoin started in
January of 2009.

00:17:32.060 --> 00:17:36.920
And nobody owned any bitcoin,
whereas Ethereum started

00:17:36.920 --> 00:17:40.955
with a presale and an ICO,
which we'll be talking about,

00:17:40.955 --> 00:17:44.530
about 72 million Ethereum.

00:17:44.530 --> 00:17:47.950
Vatalik wanted to raise money
he was maybe 19 years old.

00:17:47.950 --> 00:17:49.870
He looped in with a
venture capitalist

00:17:49.870 --> 00:17:54.460
from Canada, Joe Lubin,
who now runs ConsenSys.

00:17:54.460 --> 00:17:59.640
Lubin took about 10% or 9
and 1/2% of the offering.

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:01.990
They put 9 and 1/2%
in a foundation

00:18:01.990 --> 00:18:04.720
called the Ethereum Foundation.

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:07.930
And the other 80% was sold to
the public for $18 million.

00:18:10.732 --> 00:18:12.670
We'll talk later
in the semester as

00:18:12.670 --> 00:18:15.100
to whether that was really
a securities offering.

00:18:15.100 --> 00:18:20.110
I've publicly said I think
so, but that was in 2014.

00:18:20.110 --> 00:18:23.170
And in 2018, the Securities
and Exchange Commission

00:18:23.170 --> 00:18:26.680
has said regardless of why
it might have been in '14,

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:28.840
it's now sufficiently
decentralized

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:31.300
that we'll consider
it not a security.

00:18:31.300 --> 00:18:33.280
But in essence, they
raised $18 million

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:37.046
and were off to the races.

00:18:37.046 --> 00:18:41.810
Oh, and the 10% that Joe Lubin
kept, if he still owned it,

00:18:41.810 --> 00:18:44.100
would be worth about
$2 billion now.

00:18:44.100 --> 00:18:48.180
But he probably sold
some of it along the way.

00:18:48.180 --> 00:18:50.090
There are block rewards.

00:18:50.090 --> 00:18:53.690
The monetary policy in
Ethereum, if you remember,

00:18:53.690 --> 00:18:56.900
it splits every four years.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:58.570
There's the block reward splits.

00:18:58.570 --> 00:19:03.860
Ethereum was set up that it
was five Ether per block.

00:19:03.860 --> 00:19:06.050
And then a year ago,
they just announced

00:19:06.050 --> 00:19:07.760
they were going to
change the software

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:10.040
to three Ether per block.

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:11.720
And a month ago, they
announced they're

00:19:11.720 --> 00:19:13.760
going to change it to
two Ether per block.

00:19:13.760 --> 00:19:18.500
So the monetary policy of
bitcoin is said to be immutable

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:20.210
and fixed forever.

00:19:20.210 --> 00:19:23.750
But I would say that because
Ethereum supposedly was fixed

00:19:23.750 --> 00:19:27.800
and now, twice, they've
changed the monetary policy,

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:32.240
there is a form that if all
the miners and all the computer

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:35.420
nodes decide, they can
change the monetary policy.

00:19:35.420 --> 00:19:39.050
And Ethereum has shown that.

00:19:39.050 --> 00:19:41.750
I think Ethereum's a
bit more centralized

00:19:41.750 --> 00:19:44.990
and has more leadership,
because Vatalik Buterin

00:19:44.990 --> 00:19:49.820
is an actual human who is
willing to disclose who he is.

00:19:49.820 --> 00:19:52.730
And he still has the sort
of founder following.

00:19:52.730 --> 00:19:54.650
And Satoshi Nakamoto went--

00:19:54.650 --> 00:19:57.440
he ghosted all of
us, in a sense.

00:19:57.440 --> 00:20:00.910
And so thus, it's in some
ways socially just more

00:20:00.910 --> 00:20:04.050
decentralized.

00:20:04.050 --> 00:20:07.950
And then fees are
voluntary in bitcoin.

00:20:07.950 --> 00:20:12.880
They're a necessary part
to channel everything.

00:20:12.880 --> 00:20:13.380
Emily.

00:20:13.380 --> 00:20:15.150
AUDIENCE: Going back
to monetary policy,

00:20:15.150 --> 00:20:17.360
in practice, what
does it actually mean

00:20:17.360 --> 00:20:20.850
for a difference between bitcoin
and Ethereum that it's fixed

00:20:20.850 --> 00:20:23.440
but changing versus
staying at the same rate?

00:20:23.440 --> 00:20:25.860
PROFESSOR: So Emily asks,
what does it mean in practice?

00:20:25.860 --> 00:20:33.300
In practice, bitcoin has a much
slower growth rate or inflation

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:40.230
rate, which is currently, if
I'm not mistaken, about half.

00:20:40.230 --> 00:20:41.130
What's that?

00:20:41.130 --> 00:20:42.190
About 4%.

00:20:42.190 --> 00:20:46.590
But it's about half of the
inflation rate at Ethereum,

00:20:46.590 --> 00:20:49.830
which is running
in the 7% range.

00:20:49.830 --> 00:20:53.670
Every one of the
1,600 live tokens

00:20:53.670 --> 00:20:55.500
that are right
now Ott coins have

00:20:55.500 --> 00:20:57.210
separate monetary policies.

00:20:57.210 --> 00:20:59.220
And one could do a
complete economic study

00:20:59.220 --> 00:21:00.660
about what it means.

00:21:00.660 --> 00:21:02.970
But in terms of
Ethereum versus bitcoin,

00:21:02.970 --> 00:21:07.140
Ethereum has a higher
inflation rate.

00:21:07.140 --> 00:21:09.270
And secondly,
because they've shown

00:21:09.270 --> 00:21:13.650
that they can form some
consensus and change it,

00:21:13.650 --> 00:21:15.780
I think it sends an
interesting question

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:21.780
into that ecosystem as to how
hard a monetary policy versus

00:21:21.780 --> 00:21:27.130
a more human-based,
flexible monetary policy.

00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:28.180
Hugo.

00:21:28.180 --> 00:21:31.840
AUDIENCE: So is it that the
core developers of the Ethereum

00:21:31.840 --> 00:21:33.822
blockchain decide?

00:21:33.822 --> 00:21:36.280
I'm not familiar with how they
make that decision to change

00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:37.520
the monetary policy.

00:21:37.520 --> 00:21:41.350
PROFESSOR: So the core
developers of any coin

00:21:41.350 --> 00:21:44.560
can propose to the
various mining and nodes

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:50.510
to make a change, including
the monetary policy.

00:21:50.510 --> 00:21:53.290
Even in bitcoin,
the monetary policy

00:21:53.290 --> 00:21:56.230
could change if
there was a proposal

00:21:56.230 --> 00:21:58.300
from the core developers.

00:21:58.300 --> 00:22:01.480
In the Ethereum case,
they have done that twice.

00:22:01.480 --> 00:22:03.160
The core development
of Ethereum is

00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:07.720
highly concentrated around
the Ethereum Foundation.

00:22:07.720 --> 00:22:11.110
ConsenSys, the company
that Joe Lubin runs,

00:22:11.110 --> 00:22:15.970
has some normative social
standing in the community,

00:22:15.970 --> 00:22:18.070
as well.

00:22:18.070 --> 00:22:20.650
But it's been part of proposals.

00:22:20.650 --> 00:22:25.780
And in reading the proposals, it
goes back to Emily's question.

00:22:25.780 --> 00:22:28.540
The core developers have said we
should bring down the inflation

00:22:28.540 --> 00:22:29.350
rate.

00:22:29.350 --> 00:22:32.570
There's an active advocacy to
bring down the inflation rate.

00:22:32.570 --> 00:22:35.000
AUDIENCE: So you go by
updating your node software?

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:36.790
PROFESSOR: Yes, in essence.

00:22:36.790 --> 00:22:39.880
And it could lead to a
hard fork, I believe.

00:22:42.588 --> 00:22:43.630
So that's the background.

00:22:43.630 --> 00:22:45.172
Let me just talk
about the platforms.

00:22:45.172 --> 00:22:47.230
We know about Ethereum.

00:22:47.230 --> 00:22:48.550
We've just chatted about it.

00:22:48.550 --> 00:22:51.910
Its actual current market
value is $22 billion.

