00:34:40.449 --> 00:34:43.000
about the nature
of the law as it

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:46.360
might interact with the issues
around digital contracts.

00:34:46.360 --> 00:34:47.679
So I teach contracts.

00:34:47.679 --> 00:34:50.230
Contract law is one of the
subjects which I've taught

00:34:50.230 --> 00:34:52.630
since I started teaching.

00:34:52.630 --> 00:34:55.600
And so I want to frame
four points for you

00:34:55.600 --> 00:34:57.550
about how to think
about contract law

00:34:57.550 --> 00:35:02.055
as it relates to these
potential digital contracts.

00:35:02.055 --> 00:35:03.430
But the first
thing to do is just

00:35:03.430 --> 00:35:04.720
to make sure we
understand we're all

00:35:04.720 --> 00:35:06.040
talking about the same thing.

00:35:06.040 --> 00:35:06.540
OK.

00:35:06.540 --> 00:35:11.320
So here's what the
core of contract law

00:35:11.320 --> 00:35:14.640
teaches us contracts are.

00:35:14.640 --> 00:35:17.130
Contract is a promise
or performance

00:35:17.130 --> 00:35:22.130
given in exchange for a
promise or performance.

00:35:22.130 --> 00:35:24.770
"Given in exchange for"
is really critical.

00:35:24.770 --> 00:35:26.960
That's the quid pro
quo that's sometimes

00:35:26.960 --> 00:35:30.950
referred to as the
consideration for the promise.

00:35:30.950 --> 00:35:32.532
But notice here,
this is mapping out

00:35:32.532 --> 00:35:33.740
four different possibilities.

00:35:33.740 --> 00:35:36.800
You can have a promise in
exchange for a promise.

00:35:36.800 --> 00:35:40.780
I promise to pay you $10,000
if you promise to sing

00:35:40.780 --> 00:35:43.450
an opera for me tomorrow.

00:35:43.450 --> 00:35:46.150
Or it can be a promise
for a performance.

00:35:46.150 --> 00:35:52.100
I promise to pay you, Andy, $5
if you sing a song for us now.

00:35:52.100 --> 00:35:54.110
So it's the performance I want.

00:35:54.110 --> 00:35:56.110
I don't want a promise
from him, because we know

00:35:56.110 --> 00:35:58.780
what Andy's promises are worth.

00:35:58.780 --> 00:36:00.670
Or it could be a
performance for a promise.

00:36:00.670 --> 00:36:05.350
I'll sing if you promise
to pay me after I'm done.

00:36:05.350 --> 00:36:07.330
Or the really interesting
one for our purposes

00:36:07.330 --> 00:36:11.260
is a performance
for a performance.

00:36:11.260 --> 00:36:14.790
I'll sing if you pay me $5,000.

00:36:14.790 --> 00:36:17.290
I didn't want a promise from
you, because I don't trust you.

00:36:17.290 --> 00:36:18.730
You're business school students.

00:36:18.730 --> 00:36:21.790
So I just want the money.

00:36:21.790 --> 00:36:23.458
But I'm not promising
to do anything.

00:36:23.458 --> 00:36:25.250
I'm actually going to
do something for you.

00:36:25.250 --> 00:36:27.370
Now, that's the one
that we're going

00:36:27.370 --> 00:36:30.407
to think about in the
context of digital contracts.

00:36:30.407 --> 00:36:30.990
Oh, I'm sorry.

00:36:30.990 --> 00:36:34.718
Let me just fix one thing here.

00:36:34.718 --> 00:36:36.510
Actually, I was going
to make three points,

00:36:36.510 --> 00:36:37.880
but then I decided I
was going to make four.

00:36:37.880 --> 00:36:38.672
So let me fix that.

00:36:38.672 --> 00:36:40.962
Four points about contracts.

00:36:40.962 --> 00:36:42.420
So the first point
about contracts,

00:36:42.420 --> 00:36:45.035
so think about this case.

00:36:45.035 --> 00:36:46.830
All right.

00:36:46.830 --> 00:36:49.990
It's not quite digital, but
it's a physical contract

00:36:49.990 --> 00:36:55.640
machine in the sense that it's
a performance for a performance.

00:36:55.640 --> 00:36:59.630
If you drop a dime
into this machine,

00:36:59.630 --> 00:37:04.590
then out will come Dr.
Pepper or something else.

00:37:04.590 --> 00:37:05.090
OK.

00:37:05.090 --> 00:37:08.960
So there's no promises involved.

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:10.940
And we understand there's
a mechanism that's

00:37:10.940 --> 00:37:14.180
to produce this result.
And obviously, these

00:37:14.180 --> 00:37:16.860
have been here for a long time.

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:19.070
And these mechanisms
provide real value,

00:37:19.070 --> 00:37:21.920
because to the extent you
don't have to hire somebody

00:37:21.920 --> 00:37:25.400
to stand there handing
out Dr. Peppers,

00:37:25.400 --> 00:37:28.490
you can lower the cost
of delivering Dr. Peppers

00:37:28.490 --> 00:37:30.230
and increase the
market for Dr. Pepper.

00:37:30.230 --> 00:37:32.450
So this is the
motivation-- lower

00:37:32.450 --> 00:37:34.430
the transaction
costs of engaging

00:37:34.430 --> 00:37:36.980
in a particular kind
of contract, which

00:37:36.980 --> 00:37:38.690
is performance for performance.

00:37:38.690 --> 00:37:40.190
Now, when you look
at that contract,

00:37:40.190 --> 00:37:44.750
you should ask yourself, what
are the terms of this contract?

00:37:44.750 --> 00:37:45.250
All right.

00:37:45.250 --> 00:37:47.710
So some of them are express,
and they're pretty obvious.

00:37:47.710 --> 00:37:48.830
So this says $0.10.

00:37:48.830 --> 00:37:56.580
It says if you pay $0.10,
you will get the Dr. Pepper.

00:37:56.580 --> 00:37:58.020
Or that's what you
kind of expect.

00:37:58.020 --> 00:38:00.540
There's a great cartoon I
couldn't find where you come

00:38:00.540 --> 00:38:02.860
to a machine that
says deposit $0.50.

00:38:02.860 --> 00:38:04.920
Deposits $0.50, and
the light comes on.

00:38:04.920 --> 00:38:07.690
It says, thank you very much.

00:38:07.690 --> 00:38:08.190
Right.

00:38:08.190 --> 00:38:10.950
So you think you know
what this contract is,

00:38:10.950 --> 00:38:13.915
but that joke hints
that maybe you don't

00:38:13.915 --> 00:38:15.040
know what that contract is.

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:17.610
But the express terms
of the one we expect

00:38:17.610 --> 00:38:20.370
go with a statement,
the machine.

00:38:20.370 --> 00:38:23.630
But then there's a whole
bunch of implied terms.

00:38:23.630 --> 00:38:27.310
So one implied term if this
machine is in the United States

00:38:27.310 --> 00:38:31.270
is that when you take the Dr.
Pepper out and you drink it,

00:38:31.270 --> 00:38:34.000
it's actually going
to be safe to drink.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:35.770
It's actually going
to be Dr. Pepper.

00:38:35.770 --> 00:38:38.360
It's actually not
going to make you sick.

00:38:38.360 --> 00:38:42.350
And none of that is written
on the Dr. Pepper machine.

00:38:42.350 --> 00:38:45.590
That's instead a
term, a contract term,

00:38:45.590 --> 00:38:51.200
that gets created by the law
and gets imposed or wrapped

00:38:51.200 --> 00:38:56.310
around the delivery
of that drink.

00:38:56.310 --> 00:38:56.810
OK.

00:38:56.810 --> 00:38:57.750
That's their first point.

00:38:57.750 --> 00:38:59.125
The second point
is to think more

00:38:59.125 --> 00:39:01.220
about what these
implied terms imply.

00:39:03.970 --> 00:39:10.150
Because if these implied terms
are implied by a legal system,

00:39:10.150 --> 00:39:12.700
then that means the
legal system has

00:39:12.700 --> 00:39:16.340
an interest in your contract.

00:39:16.340 --> 00:39:20.940
Legal system is
not undisinterested

00:39:20.940 --> 00:39:21.690
in your contract.

00:39:21.690 --> 00:39:23.370
So we should always
think that our contract

00:39:23.370 --> 00:39:24.630
is going to have two parties.

00:39:24.630 --> 00:39:28.080
We call them the promisor
and the promisee.

00:39:28.080 --> 00:39:29.910
I've told you
we've had contracts

00:39:29.910 --> 00:39:30.955
that can be performance.

00:39:30.955 --> 00:39:32.580
"The performancer"
isn't really a word.

00:39:32.580 --> 00:39:34.710
But let's just say
promisor and promisee.

00:39:34.710 --> 00:39:36.160
But there's always
a third party,

00:39:36.160 --> 00:39:39.060
which is the state, who is
in the middle of the contract

00:39:39.060 --> 00:39:44.430
in the sense that the state
will police many contracts

00:39:44.430 --> 00:39:48.130
and decide whether the state
likes the contract or not.

00:39:48.130 --> 00:39:51.060
And if the state doesn't
like the contract,

00:39:51.060 --> 00:39:53.700
then the state won't
enforce the contract.

00:39:53.700 --> 00:39:55.440
Or the state might
actually punish you

00:39:55.440 --> 00:39:56.800
because of the contract.

00:39:56.800 --> 00:40:01.380
So for example, the state cares
about the kinds of contracts.

00:40:01.380 --> 00:40:03.540
You can have contracts
for the sale of tables.

00:40:03.540 --> 00:40:05.800
You can't have contracts
for the sale of people.

00:40:05.800 --> 00:40:08.340
But you can sell dogs for
reasons I can't understand.

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:11.310
But the point is we are
deciding which type of things

00:40:11.310 --> 00:40:14.610
can be sold and which kind
of things can't be sold.

00:40:14.610 --> 00:40:18.780
The state cares about the
effect of the contract.

00:40:18.780 --> 00:40:22.650
If the contract is to
render your corporation

00:40:22.650 --> 00:40:25.493
vulnerable to
bankruptcy, the state

00:40:25.493 --> 00:40:26.910
might have an
interest in deciding

00:40:26.910 --> 00:40:28.700
whether that contract
will be enforced

00:40:28.700 --> 00:40:30.450
or not or whether it'll
be allowed or not,

00:40:30.450 --> 00:40:34.140
whether it's permissible
under bankruptcy laws

00:40:34.140 --> 00:40:36.390
to engage in that contract
because of the risk

00:40:36.390 --> 00:40:37.610
that it's going to create.

00:40:37.610 --> 00:40:41.900
The state's going to care about
the terms of the contract.

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:48.700
So if you're selling your labor
in a state with a minimum wage

00:40:48.700 --> 00:40:50.110
law, the state's going to care.

00:40:50.110 --> 00:40:54.100
Does the term that
specifies your wage equal

00:40:54.100 --> 00:40:56.680
or exceed the minimum wage?

00:40:56.680 --> 00:40:59.530
And states can obviously
care-- the most important thing

00:40:59.530 --> 00:41:01.300
for the state is whether
and how the state

00:41:01.300 --> 00:41:03.440
taxes the transaction
in the contract.

00:41:03.440 --> 00:41:07.463
So when does it tax
the transaction?

00:41:07.463 --> 00:41:09.380
What is the event that's
going to manifest it?

00:41:09.380 --> 00:41:11.360
And of course, the
contract can try

00:41:11.360 --> 00:41:15.148
to play with that sort of deal
with whether it will be taxed.

00:41:15.148 --> 00:41:17.690
And the state will care about
how the contract deals with it.

00:41:17.690 --> 00:41:18.190
OK.

00:41:18.190 --> 00:41:24.120
So the point is to fight
against the first real bias

00:41:24.120 --> 00:41:28.220
that especially,
let's say, tech people

00:41:28.220 --> 00:41:29.900
and maybe business
tech people bring

00:41:29.900 --> 00:41:32.563
to the idea of contract law,
which is that contracts are not

00:41:32.563 --> 00:41:33.230
about the state.

00:41:33.230 --> 00:41:35.480
They're about private parties.

00:41:35.480 --> 00:41:36.230
That's not true.

00:41:36.230 --> 00:41:39.290
They're about private
parties and the state.

00:41:39.290 --> 00:41:41.470
And the state is always
going to be there.

00:41:41.470 --> 00:41:44.810
Now, so if I say
to you, I'm trying

00:41:44.810 --> 00:41:46.010
to sell my parents' house.

00:41:46.010 --> 00:41:46.820
I can't sell it.

00:41:46.820 --> 00:41:48.290
So if I say to
you, I'll offer you

00:41:48.290 --> 00:41:52.460
$10,000 to anyone who will
burn down my parents' house.

00:41:52.460 --> 00:41:54.752
You're trying to
accept that contract.

00:41:54.752 --> 00:41:56.960
You're raising your hand,
so you're trying to accept.

00:41:56.960 --> 00:41:59.510
I want to say officially
it's a joke so nobody gets

00:41:59.510 --> 00:42:00.953
any uncertainty about this.

00:42:00.953 --> 00:42:02.870
Now, you're going to ask
a question, because I

00:42:02.870 --> 00:42:03.953
didn't want you to accept.

00:42:03.953 --> 00:42:06.350
Because if you accepted
my offer, then that's it.

00:42:06.350 --> 00:42:06.980
I'm stuck.

00:42:06.980 --> 00:42:09.230
So now it's clear it's
not really an offer,

00:42:09.230 --> 00:42:11.460
and I can ask you a question.

00:42:11.460 --> 00:42:14.517
AUDIENCE: So you said contracts
cannot be between two parties.

00:42:14.517 --> 00:42:16.600
They have to be between
two parties and the state.

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:17.308
LARRY LESSIG: No.

00:42:17.308 --> 00:42:19.040
So let me say it more clearly.

00:42:19.040 --> 00:42:22.610
Contracts always have
the state present,

00:42:22.610 --> 00:42:24.198
so it's always
between two parties

00:42:24.198 --> 00:42:25.240
or three parties or four.

00:42:25.240 --> 00:42:26.900
So you and I enter
into a contract.

00:42:26.900 --> 00:42:29.870
Not this one, but another one.

00:42:29.870 --> 00:42:33.350
But the state is in
the room and deciding

00:42:33.350 --> 00:42:36.450
whether the state's going to
allow the contract to happen.

00:42:36.450 --> 00:42:38.450
So most contracts, the
state doesn't care about.

00:42:38.450 --> 00:42:40.370
But some contracts, the
state's going to say,

00:42:40.370 --> 00:42:43.600
hell no, we're not going
to allow it, like this one.

00:42:43.600 --> 00:42:46.347
If you didn't get that
notice it was a joke

00:42:46.347 --> 00:42:48.430
and you thought I was
serious and you went and you

00:42:48.430 --> 00:42:51.097
burned down my parents' house so
that we could get the insurance

00:42:51.097 --> 00:42:53.410
and not have to worry
about selling the house,

00:42:53.410 --> 00:42:56.590
and then you came to me, and
you said, OK, pay the $10,000.

00:42:56.590 --> 00:42:58.240
And I said, it was
an obvious joke.

00:42:58.240 --> 00:43:00.850
And you went to a court,
and you said, force Lessig

00:43:00.850 --> 00:43:02.800
to pay the $10,000.

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:05.450
The court will say this
is an illegal contract.

00:43:05.450 --> 00:43:07.390
I'm not going to
enforce this contract.

00:43:07.390 --> 00:43:09.550
So my point is the state,
in a certain sense,

00:43:09.550 --> 00:43:12.830
is the censor of this contract.

00:43:12.830 --> 00:43:15.640
The state is in the room
when we make this contract.

00:43:15.640 --> 00:43:17.170
And the state's
judgment about it

00:43:17.170 --> 00:43:20.390
will decide whether
we enforce it or not.

00:43:20.390 --> 00:43:22.260
Is that clearer?

00:43:22.260 --> 00:43:24.802
AUDIENCE: So you're not saying
the state has to be there.

00:43:24.802 --> 00:43:27.010
LARRY LESSIG: I'm not saying
the state is technically

00:43:27.010 --> 00:43:28.600
signing the document.

00:43:28.600 --> 00:43:30.550
But I'm getting you
to recognize the fact

00:43:30.550 --> 00:43:35.130
that the contract is valuable
to the extent it's enforceable.

00:43:35.130 --> 00:43:38.870
And the state is the
essential agent in enforcement

00:43:38.870 --> 00:43:40.365
in the real world.

00:43:40.365 --> 00:43:42.740
AUDIENCE: So I guess that's
my question, because it seems

00:43:42.740 --> 00:43:46.510
like nowadays, we can have
contracts where the enforcement

00:43:46.510 --> 00:43:48.380
is not the state.

00:43:48.380 --> 00:43:50.190
I can put a contract
out there that says,

00:43:50.190 --> 00:43:51.860
hey, if you can
factor this number,

00:43:51.860 --> 00:43:54.664
give me the prime factors of
it, I'll give you 10 Ether.

00:43:54.664 --> 00:43:55.456
LARRY LESSIG: Yeah.

00:43:55.456 --> 00:43:57.950
And what I started with
when I was showing you

00:43:57.950 --> 00:44:01.100
this picture was to
say, actually, that's

00:44:01.100 --> 00:44:02.900
been true for a while, right?

00:44:02.900 --> 00:44:05.925
So in what sense
is the state here?

00:44:05.925 --> 00:44:08.050
Well, the state is here if
when you put the dime in

00:44:08.050 --> 00:44:10.400
and you get the drink out and
the drink doesn't have Dr.

00:44:10.400 --> 00:44:12.467
Pepper but it has
gasoline in it,

00:44:12.467 --> 00:44:14.300
the state would come
in and say, whoa, wait.

00:44:14.300 --> 00:44:17.090
You've breached the
implied term that said

00:44:17.090 --> 00:44:19.110
that this was safe to consume.

00:44:19.110 --> 00:44:21.980
So the state is in
this contract, too.

00:44:21.980 --> 00:44:24.680
And so what I'm trying to
lead to or get to the place

00:44:24.680 --> 00:44:27.770
where we say, is there ever a
place where the state is not

00:44:27.770 --> 00:44:33.950
there, which is what I think
your blockchain-like invocation

00:44:33.950 --> 00:44:34.760
is.

00:44:34.760 --> 00:44:38.140
So that's a question we're
going to get to in a second.

00:44:38.140 --> 00:44:39.140
Here's another contract.

00:44:42.380 --> 00:44:47.570
We'll offer you $50,000 to
lobby Congress to pass HR102.

00:44:47.570 --> 00:44:50.540
This contract looks
pretty normal to us.

00:44:50.540 --> 00:44:53.870
You can imagine lobbyists
have a contract like this

00:44:53.870 --> 00:44:55.440
all the time.

00:44:55.440 --> 00:44:57.380
In fact, in the middle
of the 19th century,

00:44:57.380 --> 00:44:59.270
the Supreme Court
ruled this contract

00:44:59.270 --> 00:45:01.130
was an illegal contract.

00:45:01.130 --> 00:45:04.590
You weren't allowed to hire
people to lobby Congress,

00:45:04.590 --> 00:45:05.090
right?

00:45:05.090 --> 00:45:07.490
So again, the
background norm of what

00:45:07.490 --> 00:45:11.030
is appropriate or not for the
contract controlled what type

00:45:11.030 --> 00:45:12.270
of contracting was allowed.

00:45:12.270 --> 00:45:12.770
OK.

00:45:12.770 --> 00:45:15.020
So that's about the
type of contract.

00:45:15.020 --> 00:45:17.160
But then think about the
terms of the contract.

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:20.090
And so now, I want to
get you to recognize

00:45:20.090 --> 00:45:25.430
the way in which the terms
that the law wants a contract

00:45:25.430 --> 00:45:30.383
to have can be defeated
or not by technology.

00:45:30.383 --> 00:45:32.550
And the way I'm going to
get you to think about that

00:45:32.550 --> 00:45:35.490
is to think about not contract
law but something that

00:45:35.490 --> 00:45:37.530
will create the intuitions
I want you to have.

00:45:37.530 --> 00:45:38.880
Think about copyright law.

00:45:38.880 --> 00:45:40.440
Everybody knows
copyright law, right?

00:45:40.440 --> 00:45:43.720
I hope you know something
about copyright law.

00:45:43.720 --> 00:45:47.310
So copyright law is a basic
contract with the state.

00:45:47.310 --> 00:45:51.570
But the state says, if
you create something,

00:45:51.570 --> 00:45:54.360
then you're going to get
an exclusive right to it

00:45:54.360 --> 00:45:56.480
or exclusive rights,
a set of rights--

00:45:56.480 --> 00:45:59.520
an inclusive right to copy,
an exclusive right to sell it,

00:45:59.520 --> 00:46:03.330
exclusive right to make
derivative works of it--

00:46:03.330 --> 00:46:05.270
for a period of time--

00:46:05.270 --> 00:46:10.530
and in America right now,
that's your life plus 70 years--

00:46:10.530 --> 00:46:13.620
subject to fair
use, meaning the law

00:46:13.620 --> 00:46:17.900
says you can't control every
use of my copyrighted work.

00:46:17.900 --> 00:46:21.480
If you want to take a book
of mine and quote a section

00:46:21.480 --> 00:46:24.720
and write a review that says,
see how idiotic Lessig is?

00:46:24.720 --> 00:46:25.940
You can do that.

00:46:25.940 --> 00:46:28.020
And I can't wrap the
book in a contract that

00:46:28.020 --> 00:46:30.990
says you're not allowed to quote
it for purposes of criticizing.

00:46:30.990 --> 00:46:33.150
I'm just not allowed to do that.

00:46:33.150 --> 00:46:36.450
So copyright law, imagine
this bundle of rights

00:46:36.450 --> 00:46:38.370
that it was offering.

00:46:38.370 --> 00:46:41.870
But now imagine something called
DRM, Digital Rights Management.

00:46:41.870 --> 00:46:42.370
All right.

00:46:42.370 --> 00:46:48.050
So DRM is a set of code that we
can wrap copyrighted material

00:46:48.050 --> 00:46:52.040
in in the process of making
it available to others

00:46:52.040 --> 00:46:56.183
across networks
and whatever else.

00:46:56.183 --> 00:46:57.600
It's pretty trivial
to see the way

00:46:57.600 --> 00:47:03.730
DRM could, in effect, destroy
the limitations on the term.

00:47:03.730 --> 00:47:06.550
You can wrap it,
encrypt it, make it

00:47:06.550 --> 00:47:08.860
so that my ability to
control it will be my ability

00:47:08.860 --> 00:47:13.370
to control it, conceivably, as
long as machines are running.

00:47:13.370 --> 00:47:15.640
If it's a
Microsoft-based system,

00:47:15.640 --> 00:47:17.360
four years later, it
won't be workable.

00:47:17.360 --> 00:47:20.680
But the point is, in
principle, it could be forever.

00:47:20.680 --> 00:47:22.630
Same thing with fair use.

00:47:22.630 --> 00:47:26.110
You can imagine it being
wrapped in a way that

00:47:26.110 --> 00:47:30.470
disables the capacity
to engage in fair use.

00:47:30.470 --> 00:47:36.090
So I make tons of
presentations all the time

00:47:36.090 --> 00:47:39.030
where I need to capture video.

00:47:39.030 --> 00:47:42.240
And I was astonished
to discover the latest

00:47:42.240 --> 00:47:46.850
round of this operating
system basically

00:47:46.850 --> 00:47:50.000
makes it incredibly
difficult to rip

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:52.310
video for the purpose
of capturing even two

00:47:52.310 --> 00:47:53.190
seconds of it.

00:47:53.190 --> 00:47:56.850
So if you have a video program
that is capturing your screen,

00:47:56.850 --> 00:47:59.540
this operating system
will now disable it

00:47:59.540 --> 00:48:01.790
for any period of
time that you're

00:48:01.790 --> 00:48:03.110
trying to capture the screen.

00:48:03.110 --> 00:48:05.660
They've built the technology
so that, now, there

00:48:05.660 --> 00:48:08.570
is no capacity,
technical capacity,

00:48:08.570 --> 00:48:10.880
to engage in fair
use of copyrighted

00:48:10.880 --> 00:48:13.880
material on the Apple platform.

00:48:13.880 --> 00:48:15.680
Now, you might say,
why should they

00:48:15.680 --> 00:48:19.610
be allowed to do that
if the law intended

00:48:19.610 --> 00:48:24.567
that the contract gives you
the free use of fair use?

00:48:24.567 --> 00:48:26.150
Why should they be
allowed to do that?

00:48:26.150 --> 00:48:29.540
But that's the battle that's
been going on about DRM

00:48:29.540 --> 00:48:32.750
ever since the beginning of
the beginning of copyrighted

00:48:32.750 --> 00:48:34.100
work on the internet.

00:48:34.100 --> 00:48:35.630
So my point is to
get you to realize

00:48:35.630 --> 00:48:42.622
the way the code becomes part
of the law of this contract.

00:48:42.622 --> 00:48:44.330
And you have to ask
yourself the question

00:48:44.330 --> 00:48:49.340
whether that law is respecting
the law of the sovereign,

00:48:49.340 --> 00:48:50.700
the law of the jurisdiction.

00:48:50.700 --> 00:48:54.170
So when Apple and
Disney get together

00:48:54.170 --> 00:48:56.420
and they sell this
technology and they

00:48:56.420 --> 00:48:59.840
sell movies across
the iTunes platform

00:48:59.840 --> 00:49:02.710
that make it
practically impossible--

00:49:02.710 --> 00:49:03.860
there's not even code.

00:49:03.860 --> 00:49:05.720
I mean, if you go out
there and you look,

00:49:05.720 --> 00:49:08.095
you can find everybody who
says, yeah, with this version,

00:49:08.095 --> 00:49:10.410
nobody's yet found
a way to break it.

00:49:10.410 --> 00:49:12.650
So right now, we're in a
world where, right now, it's

00:49:12.650 --> 00:49:15.260
not possible for me to
capture three seconds to put

00:49:15.260 --> 00:49:17.840
into a presentation.

00:49:17.840 --> 00:49:20.420
And the issue that
raises is, to what extent

00:49:20.420 --> 00:49:23.450
is that consistent
with copyright law

00:49:23.450 --> 00:49:25.370
if the technology
now disables you

00:49:25.370 --> 00:49:27.400
from doing exactly what
copyright law wants?

00:49:27.400 --> 00:49:30.440
So this is the trade-off
to think about,

00:49:30.440 --> 00:49:35.180
the relationship between the
policy that the law wants

00:49:35.180 --> 00:49:38.130
and the policy of
the technology.

00:49:38.130 --> 00:49:40.810
And there's no reason to believe
the policy of the technology

00:49:40.810 --> 00:49:44.575
will always be
consistent with the law.

00:49:44.575 --> 00:49:46.700
And to the extent it's not
consistent with the law,

00:49:46.700 --> 00:49:47.660
it challenges the law.

00:49:47.660 --> 00:49:52.940
It says to the law, OK,
come out and get me.

00:49:52.940 --> 00:49:54.920
Now, that obviously
is implicated

00:49:54.920 --> 00:49:58.420
in the context of
smart contracts,

00:49:58.420 --> 00:50:00.550
because the biggest fear
about smart contracts

00:50:00.550 --> 00:50:05.230
is that they enable a kind
of transaction that can hide

00:50:05.230 --> 00:50:07.910
from the policy of the law.

00:50:07.910 --> 00:50:12.070
So the question for the law is,
what will you do to step in?

00:50:12.070 --> 00:50:14.390
And this is, I think, where
your question was going.

00:50:14.390 --> 00:50:17.970
How does the state appear in
the middle of that contract?

00:50:17.970 --> 00:50:21.760
But let's take one more
step before we get to that.

00:50:21.760 --> 00:50:22.260
OK.

00:50:22.260 --> 00:50:23.450
That's the second point.

00:50:23.450 --> 00:50:26.240
Here's the third point.

00:50:26.240 --> 00:50:29.330
There's often this intuition
that, especially technologists,

00:50:29.330 --> 00:50:31.720
people have about what the
particular aim of contract law

00:50:31.720 --> 00:50:31.910
is.

00:50:31.910 --> 00:50:33.410
So in the very
beginning of me writing

00:50:33.410 --> 00:50:35.410
about the law of cyberspace,
somebody from MIT--

00:50:35.410 --> 00:50:37.460
I won't name any
names-- it wasn't Andy--

00:50:37.460 --> 00:50:40.140
showed up at the Harvard
Law School and said,

00:50:40.140 --> 00:50:42.328
I've solved the problem
of contract law.

00:50:42.328 --> 00:50:43.370
I said, what do you mean?

00:50:43.370 --> 00:50:46.580
He said, I have a system
that will eliminate risks

00:50:46.580 --> 00:50:48.562
in contracts.

00:50:48.562 --> 00:50:50.770
And he was really disappointed
when I said, you know,

00:50:50.770 --> 00:50:54.380
the objective of contract law
is not to eliminate risks.

00:50:54.380 --> 00:50:57.010
The objective of contract
law is just to allocate risk,

00:50:57.010 --> 00:50:59.722
to figure out who has
the risk, so each of us

00:50:59.722 --> 00:51:01.680
can figure out what to
do in light of the risk.

00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:05.540
So if I say I will buy
10,000 bushels of corn

00:51:05.540 --> 00:51:07.520
from you at $350 a bushel--

00:51:07.520 --> 00:51:09.680
turns out that is the
price of corn right now.

00:51:09.680 --> 00:51:11.430
He always looks up
things on the internet.

00:51:11.430 --> 00:51:13.000
I figure I should look it
up before I present it.

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:15.630
So $350 is the price of a bushel
of corn right now delivered

00:51:15.630 --> 00:51:18.120
September 1.

00:51:18.120 --> 00:51:20.610
What that's basically
doing is it's allocating

00:51:20.610 --> 00:51:22.510
the risk of the price of corn.

00:51:22.510 --> 00:51:24.390
So if you're a
farmer and you don't

00:51:24.390 --> 00:51:28.080
want to face the risk the price
of corn is going to fall to $3,

00:51:28.080 --> 00:51:30.480
you enter into this contract.

00:51:30.480 --> 00:51:33.600
If you're a buyer, you
accept this contract.

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:35.670
But if the price of
corn falls to $3,

00:51:35.670 --> 00:51:37.210
well, you're out of luck.

00:51:37.210 --> 00:51:42.960
So the point is it
relocates the price change,

00:51:42.960 --> 00:51:44.880
reallocates the risk
of price change,

00:51:44.880 --> 00:51:47.500
also reallocates the
risk of delivery.

00:51:47.500 --> 00:51:51.210
So if I've got all this corn, I
can place it in a certain place

00:51:51.210 --> 00:51:55.260
to shift the risk of delivery
so that, once again, I

00:51:55.260 --> 00:51:58.350
use the contract to
shift my risk of storage

00:51:58.350 --> 00:52:00.810
or my risk of delivery
and you on the other side.

00:52:00.810 --> 00:52:03.570
So the objective of
contract law, number one,

00:52:03.570 --> 00:52:06.090
is risk allocation.

00:52:06.090 --> 00:52:06.590
Number one.

00:52:06.590 --> 00:52:12.755
But allocation matters only if--

00:52:12.755 --> 00:52:14.600
trying to say only if for me--

00:52:14.600 --> 00:52:17.120
only if there is a
system to process

00:52:17.120 --> 00:52:23.470
the breach of a contract, only
if you've got a technology,

00:52:23.470 --> 00:52:25.243
let's say, for
processing the breach.

00:52:25.243 --> 00:52:26.660
So if I have a
contract with you--

00:52:26.660 --> 00:52:30.480
10,000 bushels of corn,
$3.50, on September 1--

00:52:30.480 --> 00:52:35.040
and you don't deliver,
that's a breach.

00:52:35.040 --> 00:52:38.400
My risk has only
been reallocated

00:52:38.400 --> 00:52:40.800
if there's some way
for me to enforce

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:42.330
the contract at that point.

00:52:42.330 --> 00:52:44.370
So it requires the system.

00:52:44.370 --> 00:52:46.290
And the system we
ordinarily take for granted

00:52:46.290 --> 00:52:48.680
is a legal system.

00:52:48.680 --> 00:52:50.060
And I say we take
it for granted,

00:52:50.060 --> 00:52:52.700
meaning some people can
take it for granted,

00:52:52.700 --> 00:52:56.710
like people in well-developed
legal contexts.

00:52:56.710 --> 00:52:59.250
But that's also to emphasized
other people can't take it

00:52:59.250 --> 00:53:00.310
for granted--

00:53:00.310 --> 00:53:03.580
so for example, people
in developing worlds.

00:53:03.580 --> 00:53:05.620
They can't take the
legal system for granted.

00:53:05.620 --> 00:53:07.790
They can't assume that if
the contract is breached,

00:53:07.790 --> 00:53:09.873
they go into a court and
say, enforce the contract

00:53:09.873 --> 00:53:11.380
or give me damages.

00:53:11.380 --> 00:53:13.240
Or if you've got a
contract between somebody

00:53:13.240 --> 00:53:15.982
in Rwanda and
somebody in Alaska,

00:53:15.982 --> 00:53:17.440
then there, too,
there's a question

00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:20.210
of whether we've got sufficient
infrastructure to develop.

00:53:20.210 --> 00:53:24.010
So the point I want to
emphasize at the end

00:53:24.010 --> 00:53:27.010
of this little
intervention is to suggest

00:53:27.010 --> 00:53:30.730
that this fact that it
takes for granted the system

00:53:30.730 --> 00:53:35.790
of enforcement shows the real
potential benefit of this class

00:53:35.790 --> 00:53:39.220
of contracting devices.

00:53:39.220 --> 00:53:41.490
Because if we think about
this as a representation

00:53:41.490 --> 00:53:44.100
of a well-developed
legal system and we

00:53:44.100 --> 00:53:47.760
think of first-world
countries as having those

00:53:47.760 --> 00:53:50.550
and we compare third-world
or developing world

00:53:50.550 --> 00:53:53.490
countries, which don't have
these well-developed legal

00:53:53.490 --> 00:53:58.335
systems, you might say that
first-world countries are

00:53:58.335 --> 00:54:00.210
better off relative to
third-world countries,

00:54:00.210 --> 00:54:01.960
because they have the
legal infrastructure

00:54:01.960 --> 00:54:04.003
to enable this risk
allocation that will enable

00:54:04.003 --> 00:54:06.420
all sorts of market transactions
to happen which otherwise

00:54:06.420 --> 00:54:08.170
wouldn't happen.

00:54:08.170 --> 00:54:12.430
But if we imagine
infrastructure like

00:54:12.430 --> 00:54:14.710
blockchain-like
infrastructures or Ethereum

00:54:14.710 --> 00:54:18.190
infrastructures
to enter the mix,

00:54:18.190 --> 00:54:20.530
providing a technical
infrastructure that

00:54:20.530 --> 00:54:24.910
doesn't require judges and
lawyers but just requires code,

00:54:24.910 --> 00:54:30.910
then that can substitute for
the legal infrastructure,

00:54:30.910 --> 00:54:33.760
provide the infrastructure
the contract needs

00:54:33.760 --> 00:54:36.520
at a much lower cost,
and thereby enable

00:54:36.520 --> 00:54:41.380
people to contract who otherwise
wouldn't rationally contract,

00:54:41.380 --> 00:54:45.730
because they could never
count on the infrastructure

00:54:45.730 --> 00:54:49.730
of the legal system to
deliver what they need.

00:54:49.730 --> 00:54:50.230
OK.

00:54:50.230 --> 00:54:52.510
So the point is this
picture is trying

00:54:52.510 --> 00:54:57.430
to say that one key value
of these technologies

00:54:57.430 --> 00:55:00.370
is that they will be a
substitute for a failed

00:55:00.370 --> 00:55:03.460
legal system or a legal system
that's not yet developed.

00:55:03.460 --> 00:55:05.890
They will provide
the infrastructure

00:55:05.890 --> 00:55:09.350
of a legal system or
the legal systems.

00:55:09.350 --> 00:55:11.110
AUDIENCE: How can they
really do anything?

00:55:11.110 --> 00:55:13.540
Because you can't make
that contract like,

00:55:13.540 --> 00:55:19.108
I will pay you $3.50 per bushel
on September 1 in Ethereum,

00:55:19.108 --> 00:55:21.400
because you're making a
statement about the real world.

00:55:21.400 --> 00:55:25.180
The Ethereum blockchain
cannot verify that I gave you

00:55:25.180 --> 00:55:25.680
the bushels.

00:55:25.680 --> 00:55:26.388
LARRY LESSIG: OK.

00:55:26.388 --> 00:55:28.850
So I've got two slides to get
to your example [INAUDIBLE]..

00:55:28.850 --> 00:55:29.350
OK.

00:55:29.350 --> 00:55:31.683
AUDIENCE: There's ways to do
it, but they're very risky,

00:55:31.683 --> 00:55:32.500
I should say.

00:55:32.500 --> 00:55:33.333
LARRY LESSIG: Right.

00:55:33.333 --> 00:55:35.320
But let's bracket it for just--

00:55:35.320 --> 00:55:37.740
I'm not sure if it's
two, but it's n slides.

00:55:37.740 --> 00:55:40.510
But n is less than
100, I promise.

00:55:40.510 --> 00:55:43.240
So just hold one second, OK?

00:55:43.240 --> 00:55:45.000
So if you say that
one function here

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:49.240
is to substitute for
a failed legal system,

00:55:49.240 --> 00:55:55.400
that suggests that the
other key opportunity here

00:55:55.400 --> 00:55:59.810
is to enable contracts where the
transaction costs right now are

00:55:59.810 --> 00:56:02.480
otherwise too high.

00:56:02.480 --> 00:56:05.530
So this is a key opportunity
to think of places where

00:56:05.530 --> 00:56:09.400
if you can lower the transaction
costs of the contract,

00:56:09.400 --> 00:56:11.343
you will enable a
contract which otherwise

00:56:11.343 --> 00:56:12.260
can't exist right now.

00:56:12.260 --> 00:56:18.040
So I'm on a scientific board
for an insurance company.

00:56:18.040 --> 00:56:20.830
So I was meeting the
president last week.

00:56:20.830 --> 00:56:24.057
And he was all excited
about a new product which

00:56:24.057 --> 00:56:26.140
they were investing in,
which was going to provide

00:56:26.140 --> 00:56:28.390
flight delay insurance.

00:56:28.390 --> 00:56:32.770
And this product was going to
be completely blockchain driven.

00:56:32.770 --> 00:56:35.410
And this is what I'm trying
to get to your point.

00:56:35.410 --> 00:56:40.420
It would trigger payments in a
completely automatic way based

00:56:40.420 --> 00:56:42.220
on the information
that's being reported

00:56:42.220 --> 00:56:44.650
from the n different sites
that are reporting information

00:56:44.650 --> 00:56:45.233
about flights.

00:56:45.233 --> 00:56:47.020
So I buy the contract.

00:56:47.020 --> 00:56:49.330
It says, if my flight is
delayed more than an hour,

00:56:49.330 --> 00:56:51.250
I get paid $200.

00:56:51.250 --> 00:56:54.910
And automatically,
as he put it, it's

00:56:54.910 --> 00:56:56.980
a no-touch product,
by which he meant

00:56:56.980 --> 00:56:59.740
no human needs to touch this
product for this contract

00:56:59.740 --> 00:57:01.185
to be enabled.

00:57:01.185 --> 00:57:02.560
It's a kind of
product that never

00:57:02.560 --> 00:57:05.530
would have been available
before, because the transaction

00:57:05.530 --> 00:57:07.742
costs of engaging it
were way too high.

00:57:07.742 --> 00:57:09.700
But now that we've lowered
the transaction cost

00:57:09.700 --> 00:57:11.800
and have an infrastructure
of trust, which

00:57:11.800 --> 00:57:14.590
is what the blockchain
is providing here,

00:57:14.590 --> 00:57:17.650
there's a huge
market that now is

00:57:17.650 --> 00:57:20.350
available for a contract
that otherwise just

00:57:20.350 --> 00:57:21.580
wasn't there before.

00:57:21.580 --> 00:57:24.190
Now, that market depends on
making a couple assumptions.

00:57:24.190 --> 00:57:27.552
You're not saying that
there's 100% certainty

00:57:27.552 --> 00:57:29.260
that everything in
that market is working

00:57:29.260 --> 00:57:31.130
the way it's supposed to work.

00:57:31.130 --> 00:57:34.370
But the point is you
don't need 100% certainty

00:57:34.370 --> 00:57:37.170
for the vast majority of
these kinds of contracts.

00:57:37.170 --> 00:57:39.470
If it gets it wrong
every once in a while,

00:57:39.470 --> 00:57:41.390
that's good enough
for government work

00:57:41.390 --> 00:57:43.310
or good enough
for airplane work.

00:57:43.310 --> 00:57:46.520
And so that's going to
be sufficient to enable

00:57:46.520 --> 00:57:50.270
the market, recognizing that
even in the legal system

00:57:50.270 --> 00:57:51.390
market, guess what?

00:57:51.390 --> 00:57:54.170
It doesn't always
get it right either.

00:57:54.170 --> 00:57:56.860
But it doesn't always enforce
the contract well either.

00:57:56.860 --> 00:57:59.030
In fact, the costs
are much, much higher

00:57:59.030 --> 00:58:00.650
to fail in the legal system.

00:58:00.650 --> 00:58:01.340
OK.

00:58:01.340 --> 00:58:03.440
So two kinds of
transaction costs.

00:58:03.440 --> 00:58:06.950
One system transaction
cost suggests

00:58:06.950 --> 00:58:10.310
that where you have less
developed legal systems,

00:58:10.310 --> 00:58:12.770
the blockchain is going to
provide a real opportunity,

00:58:12.770 --> 00:58:15.260
because you're going to
lower the transaction

00:58:15.260 --> 00:58:16.730
costs for those systems.

00:58:16.730 --> 00:58:19.390
And the other is just
contract transaction costs.

00:58:19.390 --> 00:58:22.280
There'll be a huge
explosion of markets where,

00:58:22.280 --> 00:58:26.060
right now, the contract
transaction costs are so high,

00:58:26.060 --> 00:58:28.183
and we can lower them
and thereby enable

00:58:28.183 --> 00:58:29.600
a certain kind of
transaction that

00:58:29.600 --> 00:58:30.740
otherwise wouldn't be there.

00:58:30.740 --> 00:58:31.240
OK.

00:58:31.240 --> 00:58:32.750
Final point I want to make.

00:58:32.750 --> 00:58:36.250
The other thing technologists
always love to say

00:58:36.250 --> 00:58:37.910
is the great thing
we will do when

00:58:37.910 --> 00:58:42.100
we do contract
technology is they'll

00:58:42.100 --> 00:58:44.860
solve the clarity problem.

00:58:44.860 --> 00:58:47.097
Every term will be
perfectly clear.

00:58:47.097 --> 00:58:48.680
Because you write
those contracts out,

00:58:48.680 --> 00:58:51.070
and there's all sorts of
ambiguity and vagueness,

00:58:51.070 --> 00:58:52.060
and it's a total mess.

00:58:52.060 --> 00:58:55.500
But when we've coded
all of our contracts,

00:58:55.500 --> 00:58:58.060
our smart contracts,
then we'll have

00:58:58.060 --> 00:59:00.490
perfect certainty for
every single outcome,

00:59:00.490 --> 00:59:02.987
and that will be great.

00:59:02.987 --> 00:59:04.570
And the point I want
to suggest to you

00:59:04.570 --> 00:59:10.800
is that, often, obscurity
is a real value.

00:59:10.800 --> 00:59:14.700
Obscurity is what you want,
because here's a way to see it.

00:59:14.700 --> 00:59:16.210
So imagine this is
a decision tree.

00:59:16.210 --> 00:59:17.430
And it's really
small, because I just

00:59:17.430 --> 00:59:18.420
stole it from the internet.

00:59:18.420 --> 00:59:19.920
And it doesn't have anything
to do really with what

00:59:19.920 --> 00:59:20.878
I'm talking about here.

00:59:20.878 --> 00:59:23.760
But imagine a really
complicated decision tree

00:59:23.760 --> 00:59:26.850
like this, which is to represent
all the possible things that

00:59:26.850 --> 00:59:28.950
could happen with our deal.

00:59:28.950 --> 00:59:30.240
So I want to buy the house.

00:59:30.240 --> 00:59:33.060
But what happens if the
house gets hit by a meteor?

00:59:33.060 --> 00:59:35.040
Or what happens if
you go bankrupt?

00:59:35.040 --> 00:59:37.980
All of these possible outcomes.

00:59:37.980 --> 00:59:40.950
And in principle, we could
say we should be negotiating

00:59:40.950 --> 00:59:42.217
every one of these blue dots.

00:59:42.217 --> 00:59:44.300
We should be saying, what
happens if this happens?

00:59:44.300 --> 00:59:46.230
OK, then this is what you
get, and this is what I get.

00:59:46.230 --> 00:59:47.130
What happens if that happens?

00:59:47.130 --> 00:59:47.960
What you get, what I get.

00:59:47.960 --> 00:59:48.460
OK.

00:59:48.460 --> 00:59:50.730
So imagine this
blue dot here has

00:59:50.730 --> 00:59:55.260
a 0.002% chance of happening.

00:59:55.260 --> 00:59:58.870
So you know the chance of that
happening is practically zero.

00:59:58.870 --> 01:00:02.620
And so what's the
reasonable amount of time

01:00:02.620 --> 01:00:06.420
you should spend
negotiating that term?

01:00:06.420 --> 01:00:08.320
Zero, right?

01:00:08.320 --> 01:00:10.840
Especially because if
this term is something

01:00:10.840 --> 01:00:14.775
you know he's really
worked up about

01:00:14.775 --> 01:00:17.150
and you could never come to
an agreement about that term,

01:00:17.150 --> 01:00:19.660
it would be ridiculous that
the whole contract fall apart

01:00:19.660 --> 01:00:23.440
because of this
0.002% possibility.

01:00:23.440 --> 01:00:26.650
So what contracts
do all the time

01:00:26.650 --> 01:00:28.990
is they create
these fuzzy or vague

01:00:28.990 --> 01:00:32.950
or ambiguous places as a gamble.

01:00:32.950 --> 01:00:35.210
It's like, OK, we'll go forward.

01:00:35.210 --> 01:00:39.730
We're going to just gamble
that this 0.002% outcome won't

01:00:39.730 --> 01:00:41.740
happen.

01:00:41.740 --> 01:00:44.950
Most of the time, in fact,
you can work out how often

01:00:44.950 --> 01:00:46.475
it doesn't happen, right?

01:00:46.475 --> 01:00:48.350
So most of the time,
that would be just fine.

01:00:48.350 --> 01:00:52.360
And if it turns out to
happen, then what we'll do

01:00:52.360 --> 01:00:55.090
is ask somebody--

01:00:55.090 --> 01:00:59.420
namely, a judge-- to
figure that term out.

01:00:59.420 --> 01:01:02.050
We'll say, what should that
term be interpreted as?

01:01:02.050 --> 01:01:04.240
It was ambiguous, so what
should the answer be?

01:01:04.240 --> 01:01:05.490
And the judge will look at it.

01:01:05.490 --> 01:01:08.730
And judge will say, well, it's
fair that you win or he wins.

01:01:08.730 --> 01:01:10.460
So the point is
there are many times

01:01:10.460 --> 01:01:12.002
when you ask the
question, should you

01:01:12.002 --> 01:01:14.750
negotiate a term ex ante?

01:01:14.750 --> 01:01:17.760
And the answer to
that question is no.

01:01:17.760 --> 01:01:19.640
And in those
contexts, an ambiguity

01:01:19.640 --> 01:01:24.230
is a way to negotiate it ex
post, meaning after the fact,

01:01:24.230 --> 01:01:27.790
ex post, by using the court.

01:01:27.790 --> 01:01:31.710
So as we think about these
digital smart contracts,

01:01:31.710 --> 01:01:35.120
this is why smart contracts are
referred to as dumb contracts.

01:01:35.120 --> 01:01:37.100
They're smart contracts
for the equivalent

01:01:37.100 --> 01:01:39.110
of dropping a dime
in and getting a Dr.

01:01:39.110 --> 01:01:43.250
Pepper, the sorts of things
where the possibilities are

01:01:43.250 --> 01:01:48.230
really small and narrow, or,
like my CEO was really excited,

01:01:48.230 --> 01:01:49.670
is your plane late?

01:01:49.670 --> 01:01:51.230
Yes, I get $50.

01:01:51.230 --> 01:01:52.610
No, I don't.

01:01:52.610 --> 01:01:56.480
Things where it's
relatively clear.

01:01:56.480 --> 01:01:59.360
But there's a really
important conceptual question

01:01:59.360 --> 01:02:00.860
about what happens
when we're trying

01:02:00.860 --> 01:02:05.510
to use them for the kinds of
contracts where what we want

01:02:05.510 --> 01:02:07.190
is ambiguity.

01:02:07.190 --> 01:02:14.000
Because if the very terms of
deployment of the platform

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:20.573
demand specifying all of the
outcomes in this tree, then

01:02:20.573 --> 01:02:22.490
your basic thing is a
whole bunch of contracts

01:02:22.490 --> 01:02:24.980
you're just not going to be
able to have in this space,

01:02:24.980 --> 01:02:29.570
because the cost of specifying
that tree will be higher

01:02:29.570 --> 01:02:31.500
than the benefit
of those contracts.

01:02:31.500 --> 01:02:34.670
So it's a weird sense in
which, on the one hand,

01:02:34.670 --> 01:02:37.700
I've said to you that
this technology can

01:02:37.700 --> 01:02:41.610
lower the transaction
costs of contracts.

01:02:41.610 --> 01:02:43.550
But for this kind
of contract, it

01:02:43.550 --> 01:02:47.710
can actually increase the
transaction costs of contract.

01:02:47.710 --> 01:02:49.700
Because for this
kind of contract,

01:02:49.700 --> 01:02:54.010
if it reveals the ambiguities
we need to negotiate about

01:02:54.010 --> 01:02:55.990
and those negotiating
ambiguities are just

01:02:55.990 --> 01:02:57.940
too costly for us
to negotiate, then

01:02:57.940 --> 01:03:00.160
it's going to block us
from having that contract.

01:03:00.160 --> 01:03:03.010
It forces us to see the
0.002%, and you and I

01:03:03.010 --> 01:03:04.660
have to come to terms on it.

01:03:04.660 --> 01:03:09.480
And we don't yet have a
good way to fake ambiguity.

01:03:09.480 --> 01:03:11.880
I mean, the legal
system fakes ambiguity,

01:03:11.880 --> 01:03:14.370
because we just say, oh, yeah,
yeah, we didn't see that.

01:03:14.370 --> 01:03:15.590
They saw it.

01:03:15.590 --> 01:03:17.640
He knew it when they
wrote the contract.

01:03:17.640 --> 01:03:19.690
But they don't have
to admit they knew it.

01:03:19.690 --> 01:03:25.110
But the code has to admit it
knows there's an ambiguity.

01:03:25.110 --> 01:03:27.400
And that's a hard thing to
self consciously prevent.

01:03:27.400 --> 01:03:27.900
OK.

01:03:27.900 --> 01:03:29.330
So I've given you four ideas.

01:03:29.330 --> 01:03:31.275
Happy to take
questions or abuse.

01:03:31.275 --> 01:03:33.400
Usually, I get abuse from
business school students,

01:03:33.400 --> 01:03:34.770
but OK.

01:03:34.770 --> 01:03:40.530
AUDIENCE: So what if you can
code into a contract the easy

01:03:40.530 --> 01:03:43.497
scenarios and then say else-if--

01:03:43.497 --> 01:03:44.580
LARRY LESSIG: Go to court.

01:03:44.580 --> 01:03:47.820
AUDIENCE: --go to court or
some multinational court

01:03:47.820 --> 01:03:50.598
that is the Ethereum
court or whatever.

01:03:50.598 --> 01:03:51.390
LARRY LESSIG: Yeah.

01:03:51.390 --> 01:03:56.130
And even the Ethereum court will
have to have a court above it

01:03:56.130 --> 01:03:58.760
if it wants to avoid government
saying, if you have anything

01:03:58.760 --> 01:04:01.010
to do with Ethereum, we're
going to punish you, right?

01:04:01.010 --> 01:04:03.093
So this is the sense of
which I wanted to suggest,

01:04:03.093 --> 01:04:05.670
to go back to your
first question,

01:04:05.670 --> 01:04:10.170
that if you think about it as
layers of an onion, peel layers

01:04:10.170 --> 01:04:12.420
back enough, and you're
going to, in the end,

01:04:12.420 --> 01:04:17.650
have to get to a state
in some sense, a state

01:04:17.650 --> 01:04:19.860
as an enforceable mechanism.

01:04:19.860 --> 01:04:22.500
And that enforceable
mechanism doesn't

01:04:22.500 --> 01:04:24.030
have to be for every case.

01:04:24.030 --> 01:04:26.190
Again, 99% of the time,
you drop the dime in,

01:04:26.190 --> 01:04:27.690
you get the Dr. Pepper.

01:04:27.690 --> 01:04:30.740
But there's a contingency where
you drop the dime in, and out

01:04:30.740 --> 01:04:32.220
comes a bottle of gasoline.

01:04:32.220 --> 01:04:34.053
And then you need to
go to somebody and say,

01:04:34.053 --> 01:04:35.280
you breached this contract.

01:04:35.280 --> 01:04:36.300
And that person--

01:04:36.300 --> 01:04:39.390
AUDIENCE: But if it's a contract
between somebody in Alaska

01:04:39.390 --> 01:04:41.190
and somebody in
Rwanda, you still

01:04:41.190 --> 01:04:42.490
have the question of
which state you go to.

01:04:42.490 --> 01:04:43.400
What's the jurisdiction?

01:04:43.400 --> 01:04:44.942
So I feel like there
would have to be

01:04:44.942 --> 01:04:48.078
some extranational extra-state.

01:04:48.078 --> 01:04:48.870
LARRY LESSIG: Yeah.

01:04:48.870 --> 01:04:51.090
So you will see in
these types of contracts

01:04:51.090 --> 01:04:54.180
is there'll be a whole bunch
of boilerplate that specifies

01:04:54.180 --> 01:04:56.940
choice of law, which turns out
to be a relatively easy thing

01:04:56.940 --> 01:04:59.720
to do right now, choice
of jurisdictions.

01:04:59.720 --> 01:05:01.310
For most countries,
it's pretty easy.

01:05:01.310 --> 01:05:02.768
There are standard
ways to do that.

01:05:02.768 --> 01:05:04.770
All of that will plug
in automatically.

01:05:04.770 --> 01:05:07.710
But again, all of those
are outside of the code.

01:05:07.710 --> 01:05:10.550
All of those are law.

01:05:10.550 --> 01:05:11.940
AUDIENCE: Comment
and a question.

01:05:11.940 --> 01:05:18.340
So I don't trust Vatalik
or other software engineers

01:05:18.340 --> 01:05:22.020
that they have the legal
understanding and capacity

01:05:22.020 --> 01:05:24.660
to write legally
binding contracts.

01:05:24.660 --> 01:05:29.610
So I trust the government
or I trust the court.

01:05:29.610 --> 01:05:31.500
I don't trust a
software engineer

01:05:31.500 --> 01:05:36.850
to write a proper code to
protect me or my counterparty.

01:05:36.850 --> 01:05:43.030
So what is your take on
those smart contracts?

01:05:43.030 --> 01:05:45.210
PROFESSOR: Can I add to that?

01:05:45.210 --> 01:05:48.630
Not only your take on
whether to trust but what

01:05:48.630 --> 01:05:54.000
the courts in Europe and the US
right now do if somebody says,

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:56.728
I wrote the contract,
and here's the code.

01:05:56.728 --> 01:05:58.770
LARRY LESSIG: Well, so
when you say-- let me just

01:05:58.770 --> 01:06:01.930
me understand the
question better.

01:06:01.930 --> 01:06:02.430
I'm sorry.

01:06:02.430 --> 01:06:03.635
Your name is--

01:06:03.635 --> 01:06:04.260
AUDIENCE: Hugo.

01:06:04.260 --> 01:06:05.052
LARRY LESSIG: Hugo.

01:06:05.052 --> 01:06:06.590
The way Hugo
described it, I think,

01:06:06.590 --> 01:06:10.410
is nice, with a whole bunch of
conditional statements, which

01:06:10.410 --> 01:06:11.280
is the code.

01:06:11.280 --> 01:06:13.890
So the code says,
if the plane leaves

01:06:13.890 --> 01:06:19.560
more than 30 minutes late, then
transfer $100 to his account.

01:06:19.560 --> 01:06:21.840
So you don't trust
Vatalik's system

01:06:21.840 --> 01:06:24.840
to be able to implement
that conditional?

01:06:24.840 --> 01:06:25.800
AUDIENCE: Yep.

01:06:25.800 --> 01:06:29.220
I don't understand-- I
mean, I don't know the code.

01:06:29.220 --> 01:06:31.260
I don't know if it's breakable.

01:06:31.260 --> 01:06:33.898
I don't know if Jean can
log in and change it.

01:06:33.898 --> 01:06:35.190
LARRY LESSIG: I'm sure she can.

01:06:35.190 --> 01:06:39.540
But the point is,
for most people,

01:06:39.540 --> 01:06:41.550
this is true of everything.

01:06:41.550 --> 01:06:43.110
When I say to you,
I'm a lawyer, I'm

01:06:43.110 --> 01:06:47.130
going to write the contract so
you can sell your car to Andy,

01:06:47.130 --> 01:06:48.817
you can have the same questions.

01:06:48.817 --> 01:06:50.400
You can have the
question whether Andy

01:06:50.400 --> 01:06:53.070
is going to have a way to
flip the price so instead

01:06:53.070 --> 01:06:56.340
of $10,000, it's 15,000.

01:06:56.340 --> 01:06:57.990
So this uncertainty
is everywhere.

01:06:57.990 --> 01:07:00.510
It might be Vatalik
would say, actually,

01:07:00.510 --> 01:07:04.500
there's a more robust
way to verify my code

01:07:04.500 --> 01:07:06.772
than Lessig's contract code.

01:07:06.772 --> 01:07:08.980
Because Lessig's contract
code is written in English,

01:07:08.980 --> 01:07:10.230
and we have all sorts of--

01:07:10.230 --> 01:07:12.390
but my code, you can
have independent people

01:07:12.390 --> 01:07:13.230
who verify it.

01:07:13.230 --> 01:07:18.090
So at the level of conditionals,
I'm pretty confident.

01:07:18.090 --> 01:07:20.290
What I'm not
confident about is--

01:07:20.290 --> 01:07:26.550
and I had the great pleasure
in December of 2015 spending

01:07:26.550 --> 01:07:29.610
a weekend with them,
watching that group.

01:07:29.610 --> 01:07:31.830
And it's this weird kind of--

01:07:31.830 --> 01:07:35.040
he is like the messiah
figure, and there's

01:07:35.040 --> 01:07:37.890
12 people sitting on the
floor around him listening

01:07:37.890 --> 01:07:40.150
to his every bit of wisdom.

01:07:40.150 --> 01:07:42.690
So it was inspirational
and scary at the same time,

01:07:42.690 --> 01:07:44.400
because you see how
much money is resting

01:07:44.400 --> 01:07:45.870
on this messiah's structure.

01:07:45.870 --> 01:07:48.332
But I have a lot of
confidence in their ability

01:07:48.332 --> 01:07:49.290
to do the conditionals.

01:07:49.290 --> 01:07:51.390
But I'm not so
confident that they yet

01:07:51.390 --> 01:07:55.200
thought through how it plugs
into the bigger legal story.

01:07:55.200 --> 01:07:57.450
And that's part of what I
was trying to pitch to them,

01:07:57.450 --> 01:07:58.440
that's what I'm trying--

01:07:58.440 --> 01:07:59.857
to him, and that's
what I'm trying

01:07:59.857 --> 01:08:02.926
to pitch to you, that it's
never going to be the case.

01:08:02.926 --> 01:08:05.640
I was at this conference in
Australia where I met them.

01:08:05.640 --> 01:08:08.140
And so many of the people there
were speaking the way people

01:08:08.140 --> 01:08:09.723
spoke about the
internet 20 years ago.

01:08:09.723 --> 01:08:12.250
It's like, oh, there's
the real world.

01:08:12.250 --> 01:08:13.545
We have governments.

01:08:13.545 --> 01:08:14.670
But we're going to create--

01:08:14.670 --> 01:08:15.970
like John Perry Barlow speak.

01:08:15.970 --> 01:08:18.106
We're going to create
this virtual world where

01:08:18.106 --> 01:08:19.689
there is no governments,
where we just

01:08:19.689 --> 01:08:21.040
live free of government.

01:08:21.040 --> 01:08:26.200
And it's so fucking naive
about the way this stuff works,

01:08:26.200 --> 01:08:29.470
because it's always embedded
in a real world which

01:08:29.470 --> 01:08:30.687
has a real government.

01:08:30.687 --> 01:08:32.229
And that real
government is not going

01:08:32.229 --> 01:08:35.260
to look the other way if
you're doing lots of damage

01:08:35.260 --> 01:08:36.620
or not paying your taxes.

01:08:36.620 --> 01:08:38.500
So the question isn't whether.

01:08:38.500 --> 01:08:40.936
The question is just
how and how much.

01:08:40.936 --> 01:08:42.269
PROFESSOR: Can we go back there?

01:08:42.269 --> 01:08:42.894
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:08:42.894 --> 01:08:46.360
So I have a question about,
what kind of implications

01:08:46.360 --> 01:08:50.470
do you think this technology
has to broaden access

01:08:50.470 --> 01:08:53.649
to legal services in general,
like letting people know when

01:08:53.649 --> 01:08:56.304
they're being taken advantage
or being able to provide more

01:08:56.304 --> 01:08:58.179
standard versions of
really common contracts,

01:08:58.179 --> 01:09:00.734
like employment contracts
or lease contacts

01:09:00.734 --> 01:09:01.609
and things like that?

01:09:01.609 --> 01:09:04.609
Do you think that this is going
to be a game changer for those?

01:09:04.609 --> 01:09:06.340
LARRY LESSIG: Absolutely.

01:09:06.340 --> 01:09:10.359
I mean, you've got to
muster the political will

01:09:10.359 --> 01:09:13.770
to break the monopoly
lawyers have in this space.

01:09:13.770 --> 01:09:16.359
And I'll tell you, we're going
to fight hard against it.

01:09:16.359 --> 01:09:20.260
But there is no reason
for 90% of what lawyers

01:09:20.260 --> 01:09:23.080
do to be done by lawyers.

01:09:23.080 --> 01:09:26.050
Just like if you
buy a house and you

01:09:26.050 --> 01:09:27.550
have to have a
lawyer who sits there

01:09:27.550 --> 01:09:29.520
and basically signs
documents for you.

01:09:29.520 --> 01:09:31.689
You're like, why?

01:09:31.689 --> 01:09:33.228
And the answer is
because the law

01:09:33.228 --> 01:09:35.770
has been written to require that
person to sit there and sign

01:09:35.770 --> 01:09:36.279
documents.

01:09:36.279 --> 01:09:36.700
And why?

01:09:36.700 --> 01:09:38.742
Because the people who
get paid to sign documents

01:09:38.742 --> 01:09:40.680
have corrupted the law.

01:09:40.680 --> 01:09:42.370
So there's lots to clean up.

01:09:42.370 --> 01:09:44.760
But if we can clean
it up, absolutely.

01:09:44.760 --> 01:09:48.439
99% of this stuff
ought to be automatic.

01:09:48.439 --> 01:09:51.770
And then let's get the lawyers
to focus on the hard corner

01:09:51.770 --> 01:09:54.475
cases, not on everything
that should be automatic.

01:09:54.475 --> 01:09:55.850
And that certainly
should be true

01:09:55.850 --> 01:10:00.060
not just within a jurisdiction
but across jurisdiction.

01:10:00.060 --> 01:10:03.640
AUDIENCE: Can I return to
your insurance examples?

01:10:03.640 --> 01:10:07.270
I got the idea that you could
write a smart contract that

01:10:07.270 --> 01:10:11.140
would pay you automatically
if the plane was late.

01:10:11.140 --> 01:10:14.600
But then you said it
puts it on a blockchain.

01:10:14.600 --> 01:10:17.380
Can you connect why he put it
on the blockchain as opposed

01:10:17.380 --> 01:10:21.460
to just putting it on
his disc and letting

01:10:21.460 --> 01:10:22.990
your credit card get credited?

01:10:22.990 --> 01:10:25.870
I mean, where did the
blockchain enter into that?

01:10:25.870 --> 01:10:27.790
And why did he need
a blockchain in order

01:10:27.790 --> 01:10:31.233
to maintain that statement?

01:10:31.233 --> 01:10:33.400
LARRY LESSIG: I think that
the thing that he thought

01:10:33.400 --> 01:10:34.900
he was getting out
of the blockchain

01:10:34.900 --> 01:10:39.130
is to increase the
verifiability of third parties

01:10:39.130 --> 01:10:41.750
of the actual payments
according to the data.

01:10:41.750 --> 01:10:44.380
So if I say to you, I'm
going to be paying you

01:10:44.380 --> 01:10:47.230
$500 if your plane
is an hour late

01:10:47.230 --> 01:10:51.610
and we have the data out there
about the planes being late,

01:10:51.610 --> 01:10:54.040
if he did it inside of
his insurance company,

01:10:54.040 --> 01:10:56.140
I wouldn't have any way
to know that he paid you

01:10:56.140 --> 01:10:58.060
$500 for the plane being late.

01:10:58.060 --> 01:11:00.880
But if it's in a blockchain,
there's at least conceptually

01:11:00.880 --> 01:11:02.770
a way in which we
could be doing this--

01:11:02.770 --> 01:11:04.300
not that I'm
reviewing it to you,

01:11:04.300 --> 01:11:06.060
but we could be signaling--

01:11:06.060 --> 01:11:07.310
AUDIENCE: That doesn't follow.

01:11:07.310 --> 01:11:09.670
So that depends on who
maintains the blockchain.

01:11:09.670 --> 01:11:12.220
And then at the same
time, it returns that.

01:11:12.220 --> 01:11:14.290
Suddenly, everybody
knows the cash flow

01:11:14.290 --> 01:11:16.480
of that insurance
company, which is likely

01:11:16.480 --> 01:11:17.810
not something he wants to do.

01:11:17.810 --> 01:11:20.310
LARRY LESSIG: Well, the cash
flow of the insurance company's

01:11:20.310 --> 01:11:23.020
bigger than authenticating
the truth about certain types

01:11:23.020 --> 01:11:23.660
of contracts.

01:11:23.660 --> 01:11:24.160
AUDIENCE: Well, let
us know the cash flow

01:11:24.160 --> 01:11:25.550
of that part of the business.

01:11:25.550 --> 01:11:28.780
So I mean, he may not want that.

01:11:28.780 --> 01:11:33.730
I may not want everybody to
know what planes I'm flying.

01:11:33.730 --> 01:11:35.320
So you've implied
that there's now

01:11:35.320 --> 01:11:38.610
a public blockchain that does
that to everyone to verify.

01:11:38.610 --> 01:11:40.820
LARRY LESSIG: Yeah.

01:11:40.820 --> 01:11:42.290
All I mean to argue--

01:11:42.290 --> 01:11:43.700
and I didn't
interrogate him far.

01:11:43.700 --> 01:11:45.700
I was just taking his
statement that he's doing.

01:11:45.700 --> 01:11:47.825
So I'm trying to think,
why would he want to do it?

01:11:47.825 --> 01:11:50.440
Because I had the same kind
of question you wanted to.

01:11:50.440 --> 01:11:54.580
And it's just that if you are
trying to create credibility

01:11:54.580 --> 01:11:55.700
around your claim--

01:11:55.700 --> 01:11:58.180
but do I have a reason to
trust this insurance company

01:11:58.180 --> 01:11:59.972
that, in fact, it's
going to be doing this?

01:11:59.972 --> 01:12:02.680
Then there's some transparency
that this enables--

01:12:02.680 --> 01:12:05.200
not necessarily the transparency
of your credit card number

01:12:05.200 --> 01:12:07.660
or your name or the
flights that you're taking,

01:12:07.660 --> 01:12:10.870
but that there was somebody who
was on this who had a contract,

01:12:10.870 --> 01:12:13.120
and we then made
this kind of payment.

01:12:13.120 --> 01:12:15.100
That would be a potential
value that he has.

01:12:15.100 --> 01:12:17.830
Now, if there's no value
from that, then you're right.

01:12:17.830 --> 01:12:20.110
The overhead of the
blockchain or public

01:12:20.110 --> 01:12:22.240
or private or
whatever is too high,

01:12:22.240 --> 01:12:24.010
and he just could do it inside.

01:12:24.010 --> 01:12:26.320
And for certain
companies, like if you

01:12:26.320 --> 01:12:29.080
went to a credible insurance
company, the credible insurance

01:12:29.080 --> 01:12:31.880
company, you probably trust
that credible insurance company.

01:12:31.880 --> 01:12:35.110
But again, if you're a not
credible insurance company,

01:12:35.110 --> 01:12:39.020
if you're a startup and you
are out there in the market

01:12:39.020 --> 01:12:40.610
and you're saying,
give me your money

01:12:40.610 --> 01:12:42.050
and I'll pay you if
the plane's late,

01:12:42.050 --> 01:12:44.050
people are going to say,
why should I trust you?

01:12:44.050 --> 01:12:45.290
And you're like, well, here.

01:12:45.290 --> 01:12:46.707
You don't really
have to trust me.

01:12:46.707 --> 01:12:48.590
Here's the data.

01:12:48.590 --> 01:12:51.710
Here's the evidence in a more
credible way than if I just

01:12:51.710 --> 01:12:53.900
published a report on
my website that I'm

01:12:53.900 --> 01:12:55.760
doing what I say I'm doing.

01:12:55.760 --> 01:12:56.983
PROFESSOR: Let's try to--

01:12:56.983 --> 01:12:59.793
AUDIENCE: He has
to escrow the $500.

01:12:59.793 --> 01:13:02.210
PROFESSOR: Andy, let's try to
get a couple more questions.

01:13:02.210 --> 01:13:05.570
But my hunch is that it's
probably a permission rather

01:13:05.570 --> 01:13:07.130
than permissionless blockchain.

01:13:07.130 --> 01:13:09.380
And it may be the
insurance company

01:13:09.380 --> 01:13:12.020
wants to ride on the
buzz of blockchain.

01:13:12.020 --> 01:13:15.140
But it's possible,
also, that he thinks

01:13:15.140 --> 01:13:17.930
that there'll be more
trust, that consumers

01:13:17.930 --> 01:13:21.560
will trust that if it's
called a blockchain.

01:13:21.560 --> 01:13:23.150
But you did an interview.

01:13:23.150 --> 01:13:24.580
You can pick who you want to--

01:13:24.580 --> 01:13:25.710
LARRY LESSIG: Right here.

01:13:25.710 --> 01:13:27.127
AUDIENCE: So proof
of performance,

01:13:27.127 --> 01:13:30.420
could this whole smart
contract solve it?

01:13:30.420 --> 01:13:33.350
So for instance, some
countries will receive--

01:13:33.350 --> 01:13:38.960
and I was talking to
Leonardo about it in Cargill,

01:13:38.960 --> 01:13:40.610
in his company.

01:13:40.610 --> 01:13:42.950
They deliver wheat
to some countries.

01:13:42.950 --> 01:13:46.340
And proof of performance
is always delayed.

01:13:46.340 --> 01:13:50.030
And hence, it becomes
a private issue.

01:13:50.030 --> 01:13:53.288
So could smart contracts
solve something like that?

01:13:53.288 --> 01:13:54.080
LARRY LESSIG: Yeah.

01:13:54.080 --> 01:13:58.820
If you had an alternative way
to credibly represent a fact--

01:13:58.820 --> 01:14:02.540
and again, this is kind of
connected to Andy's point.

01:14:02.540 --> 01:14:04.100
Is there an alternative way?

01:14:04.100 --> 01:14:06.910
And is this the alternative way?

01:14:06.910 --> 01:14:10.640
Then you lower the transaction
cost of that kind of contract,

01:14:10.640 --> 01:14:15.560
because I'm going to trust
the contracting process more

01:14:15.560 --> 01:14:20.750
if I'm confident that, in fact,
the fact that I'm not late

01:14:20.750 --> 01:14:22.250
doesn't penalize
me, or you don't

01:14:22.250 --> 01:14:23.750
penalize me claiming I'm late.

01:14:23.750 --> 01:14:26.870
So to the extent you lower
the cost of verifying

01:14:26.870 --> 01:14:29.750
facts in the world, you
increase the opportunity

01:14:29.750 --> 01:14:33.230
for certain contracts to happen
who otherwise wouldn't happen.

01:14:33.230 --> 01:14:35.360
And that's the only
trade-off that I'm

01:14:35.360 --> 01:14:37.550
trying to emphasize by
emphasizing the transaction

01:14:37.550 --> 01:14:39.510
cost part of these contracts.

01:14:39.510 --> 01:14:42.820
You had a question here?

01:14:42.820 --> 01:14:44.368
AUDIENCE: Oh, yeah.

01:14:44.368 --> 01:14:46.660
I was just saying maybe one
of the benefits of applying

01:14:46.660 --> 01:14:51.175
blockchain here would be
not for one-off transactions

01:14:51.175 --> 01:14:52.800
but for the insurance
company, perhaps,

01:14:52.800 --> 01:14:55.537
to have an aggregate
thousands of transactions

01:14:55.537 --> 01:14:56.870
where they've shown performance.

01:14:56.870 --> 01:15:00.070
And they can use this
for commercial reasons

01:15:00.070 --> 01:15:02.330
to show that, yes,
people get paid

01:15:02.330 --> 01:15:05.570
when they purchase our
insurance and get credibility

01:15:05.570 --> 01:15:08.938
for particular products.

01:15:08.938 --> 01:15:09.730
LARRY LESSIG: Yeah.

01:15:09.730 --> 01:15:11.540
You would frame that
as it would have

01:15:11.540 --> 01:15:13.880
to be that that would be
a value it was providing.

01:15:13.880 --> 01:15:15.350
Otherwise, to
Andy's point, there

01:15:15.350 --> 01:15:18.307
would be no reason
to adopt this.

01:15:18.307 --> 01:15:18.890
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:15:18.890 --> 01:15:21.017
Go on the back right.

01:15:21.017 --> 01:15:22.100
I don't remember your name

01:15:22.100 --> 01:15:24.200
AUDIENCE: Kyle.

01:15:24.200 --> 01:15:31.190
So with, I guess, easier access
to these derivative contracts,

01:15:31.190 --> 01:15:33.920
do you foresee a
world where there's

01:15:33.920 --> 01:15:37.992
a lot more leverage
in any type of market

01:15:37.992 --> 01:15:39.200
outside of financial markets?

01:15:39.200 --> 01:15:43.152
And do you foresee this creating
kind of a risk in that way?

01:15:43.152 --> 01:15:46.280
LARRY LESSIG: Well, I mean,
this is your expertise, right?

01:15:46.280 --> 01:15:49.070
Because, I mean, we already
saw in the derivatives market

01:15:49.070 --> 01:15:51.890
the fact that the
choice by policymakers

01:15:51.890 --> 01:15:54.560
was to allow it to be
an invisible market

01:15:54.560 --> 01:15:56.150
and not to regulate that market.

01:15:56.150 --> 01:16:00.487
It created all sorts of risks
that sensible people might

01:16:00.487 --> 01:16:01.820
think shouldn't have been there.

01:16:01.820 --> 01:16:03.195
And I think the
same potential is

01:16:03.195 --> 01:16:05.480
here, which is, again, to
come back to the point,

01:16:05.480 --> 01:16:07.680
don't expect there not
to be government here.

01:16:07.680 --> 01:16:10.910
I mean, to the extent
people realize this risk

01:16:10.910 --> 01:16:13.850
and don't have as much
political corrupting power

01:16:13.850 --> 01:16:15.880
as Wall Street
did in our system,

01:16:15.880 --> 01:16:17.630
we should expect
governments [INAUDIBLE]..

01:16:17.630 --> 01:16:19.640
PROFESSOR: I would say yes.

01:16:19.640 --> 01:16:23.300
Even on bitcoin, you can create
something called discrete log

01:16:23.300 --> 01:16:28.460
contracts to do contracts for
differences or derivatives.

01:16:28.460 --> 01:16:31.280
But with smart contracts,
you can put a lot of leverage

01:16:31.280 --> 01:16:33.880
into the system.

01:16:33.880 --> 01:16:35.770
And transactions
can move quickly.

01:16:35.770 --> 01:16:39.770
So I think the state will
have an interest, particularly

01:16:39.770 --> 01:16:41.120
if it grows.

01:16:41.120 --> 01:16:43.370
We probably only have time
for two more questions.

01:16:43.370 --> 01:16:46.490
And I'm still wondering,
how do courts currently look

01:16:46.490 --> 01:16:50.670
at these as a matter of law?

01:16:50.670 --> 01:16:53.820
In the late 1990s, I
was honored to work

01:16:53.820 --> 01:16:56.190
with Senator John McCain
on something which

01:16:56.190 --> 01:16:58.622
became the e-signature law.

01:16:58.622 --> 01:17:01.080
I was just playing point for
the US Department of Treasury.

01:17:01.080 --> 01:17:05.160
It was really John McCain's
law Congress was doing.

01:17:05.160 --> 01:17:06.900
But I'm wondering
how the courts today

01:17:06.900 --> 01:17:09.720
would see these contracts.

01:17:09.720 --> 01:17:12.840
Do we need something
like an e-signature law

01:17:12.840 --> 01:17:18.642
to have code accepted beyond
what e-signature accepted?

01:17:18.642 --> 01:17:19.350
LARRY LESSIG: No.

01:17:19.350 --> 01:17:22.170
I think the e-signature
infrastructure

01:17:22.170 --> 01:17:24.487
is going to be 99% of
what this system is.

01:17:24.487 --> 01:17:26.820
PROFESSOR: You mean that which
I worked on 20 years ago?

01:17:26.820 --> 01:17:26.912
LARRY LESSIG: Yeah.

01:17:26.912 --> 01:17:28.410
You solved 99% of the problem.

01:17:28.410 --> 01:17:29.618
PROFESSOR: Little did I know.

01:17:29.618 --> 01:17:30.640
LARRY LESSIG: Here, too.

01:17:30.640 --> 01:17:31.140
Yeah.

01:17:31.140 --> 01:17:34.140
I mean, that's why I
wanted to wrap this

01:17:34.140 --> 01:17:36.840
around the idea of a
soda pop machine, right?

01:17:36.840 --> 01:17:39.610
So it's nothing
new, in some sense.

01:17:39.610 --> 01:17:41.610
Contract law has always
dealt with machines that

01:17:41.610 --> 01:17:44.290
are delivering on obligations.

01:17:44.290 --> 01:17:45.960
It's just a more
sophisticated set

01:17:45.960 --> 01:17:48.540
of proofs you're going to
have to make in a court.

01:17:48.540 --> 01:17:52.410
But it's the same
underlying plot.

01:17:52.410 --> 01:17:55.700
PROFESSOR: One more question.

01:17:55.700 --> 01:17:56.280
We're MIT.

01:17:56.280 --> 01:17:57.870
We're supposed to end
five minutes early.

01:17:57.870 --> 01:17:58.260
LARRY LESSIG: Oh, OK.

01:17:58.260 --> 01:17:59.160
PROFESSOR: I don't know
what you do at Harvard.

01:17:59.160 --> 01:18:01.450
LARRY LESSIG: I don't remember.

01:18:01.450 --> 01:18:03.180
PROFESSOR: It's Harvard Law.

01:18:03.180 --> 01:18:05.500
LARRY LESSIG: Right here.

01:18:05.500 --> 01:18:08.460
AUDIENCE: So I have a little
bit of the opposite question

01:18:08.460 --> 01:18:12.660
from Elon, which is a lot of the
contracts you're talking about,

01:18:12.660 --> 01:18:14.220
simple contracts, right?

01:18:14.220 --> 01:18:16.200
You've got individuals
on one side.

01:18:16.200 --> 01:18:18.620
You've got large companies,
like your insurance company,

01:18:18.620 --> 01:18:19.570
on the other.

01:18:19.570 --> 01:18:21.610
The insurance company
can't, in fact,

01:18:21.610 --> 01:18:24.210
go through the
entire decision tree

01:18:24.210 --> 01:18:28.150
and decide what every
term is in their favor.

01:18:28.150 --> 01:18:30.530
And the law deals with
that all the time.

01:18:30.530 --> 01:18:33.230
But here, you have another
problem, which is now,

01:18:33.230 --> 01:18:34.410
it's going to be OK.

01:18:34.410 --> 01:18:36.770
It's going to be written
in computer code.

01:18:36.770 --> 01:18:39.140
How are the judges
going to deal with that?

01:18:39.140 --> 01:18:41.630
Now it's a language
that is going

01:18:41.630 --> 01:18:44.300
to be even tougher to
deal with that problem.

01:18:44.300 --> 01:18:45.930
LARRY LESSIG: Great question.

01:18:45.930 --> 01:18:47.282
And the answer is--

01:18:47.282 --> 01:18:49.490
so this is actually another
version of your question.

01:18:49.490 --> 01:18:51.890
The answer to that is
nobody knows right now.

01:18:51.890 --> 01:18:55.250
And so this issue gets raised
in a lot of parallel contexts.

01:18:55.250 --> 01:18:59.390
For example, there's a Supreme
Court Justice from California

01:18:59.390 --> 01:19:04.880
who's doing a lot of work about
the question of black boxes

01:19:04.880 --> 01:19:09.495
that predict whether you are
likely to commit a crime again.

01:19:09.495 --> 01:19:11.370
So if you're convicted
of crime, the question

01:19:11.370 --> 01:19:12.995
is whether you're
going to have parole.

01:19:12.995 --> 01:19:15.840
The parole process is supposed
to decide your likelihood

01:19:15.840 --> 01:19:17.520
of committing a crime.

01:19:17.520 --> 01:19:20.010
So these companies have
built these black boxes where

01:19:20.010 --> 01:19:21.690
you spit in every bit of data.

01:19:21.690 --> 01:19:24.060
And it comes out and says
yes, you're a criminal,

01:19:24.060 --> 01:19:25.553
or no, you're not.

01:19:25.553 --> 01:19:26.970
And then the lawyers
come forward,

01:19:26.970 --> 01:19:29.640
and they say, well, I want
to interrogate the black box.

01:19:29.640 --> 01:19:31.040
I want to know what--

01:19:31.040 --> 01:19:33.773
And the courts are completely
confused about this.

01:19:33.773 --> 01:19:35.190
Because on the one
hand, they say,

01:19:35.190 --> 01:19:37.725
no, no, this is
their trade secret.

01:19:37.725 --> 01:19:39.850
But on the other hand,
they're like, wait a minute.

01:19:39.850 --> 01:19:41.830
You can't decide whether
I have liberty or not

01:19:41.830 --> 01:19:45.048
based on these black boxes that
just spit out numbers, right?

01:19:45.048 --> 01:19:46.840
So I've got to be able
to interrogate them.

01:19:46.840 --> 01:19:47.710
Right.

01:19:47.710 --> 01:19:51.100
So this is the most
important innovation that's

01:19:51.100 --> 01:19:52.600
got to happen in the law.

01:19:52.600 --> 01:19:55.270
Lawyers have to
become technically

01:19:55.270 --> 01:19:59.140
sophisticated to be
able to read code

01:19:59.140 --> 01:20:01.630
like they read legal contracts.

01:20:01.630 --> 01:20:04.210
They have to have a conceptual
understanding of what

01:20:04.210 --> 01:20:07.990
code can do so they can
think creatively about code

01:20:07.990 --> 01:20:10.960
like they think creatively
about language, right?

01:20:10.960 --> 01:20:13.900
And one of the most
important innovations

01:20:13.900 --> 01:20:17.710
that we, like the Berkman
Center and people like that,

01:20:17.710 --> 01:20:19.870
are trying to push into
the legal environment

01:20:19.870 --> 01:20:23.680
is to insist that just
like lawyers now all study

01:20:23.680 --> 01:20:27.280
economics, because that's a core
way of thinking about the law,

01:20:27.280 --> 01:20:30.480
we also should study
basic code so we

01:20:30.480 --> 01:20:33.910
can think about this
modality of regulation.

01:20:33.910 --> 01:20:36.070
Not expect people are
going to be writing code,

01:20:36.070 --> 01:20:38.230
but at least that they
can think through it.

01:20:38.230 --> 01:20:39.280
So I completely agree.

01:20:39.280 --> 01:20:42.750
That's a fudge space that
I didn't talk about at all.

01:20:42.750 --> 01:20:45.310
But I think it's a really
important problem, thinking

01:20:45.310 --> 01:20:46.540
about whether the
legal system is going

01:20:46.540 --> 01:20:47.665
to be able to deal with it.

01:20:47.665 --> 01:20:51.340
Because if none of the
lawyers understand it, yeah.

01:20:51.340 --> 01:20:53.090
Let me just end with
one story about that.

01:20:53.090 --> 01:20:55.990
So when I first started
doing this work, talking

01:20:55.990 --> 01:20:58.150
about code and--

01:20:58.150 --> 01:21:01.620
I went to Paris 20 years
ago, and I gave a speech

01:21:01.620 --> 01:21:02.650
to some lawyer group.

01:21:02.650 --> 01:21:04.810
And I sat down after the speech.

01:21:04.810 --> 01:21:09.160
And the chairman of this legal
group sat down next to me.

01:21:09.160 --> 01:21:10.210
And I introduced myself.

01:21:10.210 --> 01:21:12.040
And he stood up, and
he grabbed my card.

01:21:12.040 --> 01:21:13.580
And he crushed it.

01:21:13.580 --> 01:21:15.430
And he threw it to the ground.

01:21:15.430 --> 01:21:18.650
And he said, I am
not a technician.

01:21:18.650 --> 01:21:20.750
And his point was
he, as a lawyer,

01:21:20.750 --> 01:21:25.310
could never accept the idea that
what he needed to understand

01:21:25.310 --> 01:21:27.150
was code.

01:21:27.150 --> 01:21:28.680
That was forbidden.

01:21:28.680 --> 01:21:30.530
It was beneath him.

01:21:30.530 --> 01:21:34.950
And I think it's a hugely
important cultural problem

01:21:34.950 --> 01:21:37.160
to integrate this
form of knowledge.

01:21:37.160 --> 01:21:39.650
Because if we don't, then the
problem you're talking about

01:21:39.650 --> 01:21:42.080
is really a huge problem.

01:21:42.080 --> 01:21:44.130
But I think we can, because
we've seen lots of--

01:21:44.130 --> 01:21:46.100
PROFESSOR: So I
want to thank you

01:21:46.100 --> 01:21:50.030
on behalf of the class,
Blockchain and Money.

01:21:50.030 --> 01:21:53.404
[APPLAUSE]

01:21:55.340 --> 01:22:00.230
I also want to say you're much
better than Christopher Lloyd.

01:22:00.230 --> 01:22:02.360
And if anybody wants
to know the joke,

01:22:02.360 --> 01:22:07.640
watch that West Wing episode
that Christopher Lloyd plays

01:22:07.640 --> 01:22:08.960
Professor Lawrence Lessig.

01:22:08.960 --> 01:22:11.000
So thank you.

01:22:11.000 --> 01:22:13.030
See you on Thursday.